  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 51ee3e37f5ded7941ab6216610f6fc67, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: Elkanah and His Family
      content: '  There was a man named Elkanah who lived in Ramah in the region
        of Zuph[[COMMENT(0)]] in the hill country of Ephraim. He was the son of Jeroham,
        son of Elihu, son of Tohu, son of Zuph, of Ephraim. '
      comments:
      - number: '1:1 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>in Ramathaim-zophim; </b>compare
          1:19.
    - title: 
      content: 'Elkanah had two wives, Hannah and Peninnah. Peninnah had children,
        but Hannah did not.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Each year Elkanah would travel to Shiloh to worship and sacrifice
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies at the Tabernacle.
        The priests of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> at that time were the two
        sons of Eli\u2014Hophni and Phinehas. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the days Elkanah presented his sacrifice, he would give portions
        of the meat to Peninnah and each of her children. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And though he loved Hannah, he would give her only one choice portion[[COMMENT(0)]]
        because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given her no children. '
      comments:
      - number: '1:5 '
        content: Or <b>And because he loved Hannah, he would give her a choice portion.
          </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'So Peninnah would taunt Hannah and make fun of her because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had kept her from having children. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Year after year it was the same\u2014Peninnah would taunt Hannah
        as they went to the Tabernacle.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>also in 1:24.</smallcaps>
        Each time, Hannah would be reduced to tears and would not even eat.  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the house of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>;
          </b>
    - title: "Hannah\u2019s Prayer for a Son"
      content: "\u201CWhy are you crying, Hannah?\u201D Elkanah would ask. \u201CWhy
        aren\u2019t you eating? Why be downhearted just because you have no children?
        You have me\u2014isn\u2019t that better than having ten sons?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: Once after a sacrificial meal at Shiloh, Hannah got up and went to
        pray. Eli the priest was sitting at his customary place beside the entrance
        of the Tabernacle.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>  </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '1:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Temple of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Hannah was in deep anguish, crying bitterly as she prayed to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And she made this vow: \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s
        Armies, if you will look upon my sorrow and answer my prayer and give me
        a son, then I will give him back to you. He will be yours for his entire
        lifetime, and as a sign that he has been dedicated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        his hair will never be cut.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:11 '
        content: Some manuscripts add <b>He will drink neither wine nor intoxicants.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'As she was praying to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, Eli watched
        her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Seeing her lips moving but hearing no sound, he thought she had been
        drinking. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMust you come here drunk?\u201D he demanded. \u201CThrow away
        your wine!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COh no, sir!\u201D she replied. \u201CI haven\u2019t been drinking
        wine or anything stronger. But I am very discouraged, and I was pouring out
        my heart to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t think I am a wicked woman! For I have been praying out
        of great anguish and sorrow.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn that case,\u201D Eli said, \u201Cgo in peace! May the God
        of Israel grant the request you have asked of him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Samuel\u2019s Birth and Dedication"
      content: "\u201COh, thank you, sir!\u201D she exclaimed. Then she went back
        and began to eat again, and she was no longer sad.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The entire family got up early the next morning and went to worship
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> once more. Then they returned home to Ramah.
        When Elkanah slept with Hannah, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> remembered
        her plea, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and in due time she gave birth to a son. She named him Samuel,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for she said, \u201CI asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for him.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:20 '
        content: "<b>Samuel </b>sounds like the Hebrew term for \u201Casked of God\u201D
          or \u201Cheard by God.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'The next year Elkanah and his family went on their annual trip to
        offer a sacrifice to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and to keep his vow. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Hannah did not go. She told her husband, \u201CWait until the
        boy is weaned. Then I will take him to the Tabernacle and leave him there
        with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> permanently.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:22 '
        content: Some manuscripts add <b>I will offer him as a Nazirite for all time.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhatever you think is best,\u201D Elkanah agreed. \u201CStay
        here for now, and may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> help you keep your
        promise.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u201D So she stayed home and nursed the
        boy until he was weaned.</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:23 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version; Masoretic Text reads <b>may
          the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span> keep his promise.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'When the child was weaned, Hannah took him to the Tabernacle in Shiloh.
        They brought along a three-year-old bull[[COMMENT(0)]] for the sacrifice
        and a basket[[COMMENT(1)]] of flour and some wine. '
      comments:
      - number: '1:24a '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls, Greek and Syriac versions; Masoretic Text
          reads <b>three bulls.</b>
      - number: '1:24b '
        content: Hebrew <b>and an ephah </b>[20 quarts or 22 liters].
    - title: 
      content: 'After sacrificing the bull, they brought the boy to Eli. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSir, do you remember me?\u201D Hannah asked. \u201CI am the
        very woman who stood here several years ago praying to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to give me this boy, and
        he has granted my request. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Hannah\u2019s Prayer of Praise"
      content: "  Then Hannah prayed:\u201CMy heart rejoices in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!The
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has made me strong.[[COMMENT(0)]]Now I have an
        answer for my enemies;I rejoice because you rescued me.  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>has exalted my horn.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'No one is holy like the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!There is no one
        besides you;there is no Rock like our God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CStop acting so proud and haughty!Don\u2019t speak with such
        arrogance!For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is a God who knows what you
        have done;he will judge your actions.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The bow of the mighty is now broken,and those who stumbled are now
        strong.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Those who were well fed are now starving,and those who were starving
        are now full.The childless woman now has seven children,and the woman with
        many children wastes away.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gives both death and life;he brings
        some down to the grave[[COMMENT(0)]] but raises others up.  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to Sheol.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> makes some poor and others rich;he
        brings some down and lifts others up.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He lifts the poor from the dustand the needy from the garbage dump.He
        sets them among princes,placing them in seats of honor.For all the earth
        is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s,and he has set the world in order.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHe will protect his faithful ones,but the wicked will disappear
        in darkness.No one will succeed by strength alone.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Those who fight against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will be shattered.He
        thunders against them from heaven;the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> judges
        throughout the earth.He gives power to his king;he increases the strength[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of his anointed one.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>he exalts the horn.</b>
    - title: "Eli\u2019s Wicked Sons"
      content: 'Then Elkanah returned home to Ramah without Samuel. And the boy served
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by assisting Eli the priest.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now the sons of Eli were scoundrels who had no respect for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "or for their duties as priests. Whenever anyone offered a sacrifice,
        Eli\u2019s sons would send over a servant with a three-pronged fork. While
        the meat of the sacrificed animal was still boiling, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the servant would stick the fork into the pot and demand that whatever
        it brought up be given to Eli\u2019s sons. All the Israelites who came to
        worship at Shiloh were treated this way. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Sometimes the servant would come even before the animal\u2019s fat
        had been burned on the altar. He would demand raw meat before it had been
        boiled so that it could be used for roasting.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The man offering the sacrifice might reply, \u201CTake as much as
        you want, but the fat must be burned first.\u201D Then the servant would
        demand, \u201CNo, give it to me now, or I\u2019ll take it by force.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the sin of these young men was very serious in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, for they treated the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s offerings
        with contempt.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Samuel, though he was only a boy, served the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        He wore a linen garment like that of a priest.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He wore a linen ephod.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Each year his mother made a small coat for him and brought it to
        him when she came with her husband for the sacrifice. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Before they returned home, Eli would bless Elkanah and his wife and
        say, \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> give you other children to
        take the place of this one she gave to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>\u201D
        </smallcaps>"
      comments:
      - number: '2:20 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version; Masoretic Text reads <b>this
          one he requested of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> blessed Hannah, and she conceived
        and gave birth to three sons and two daughters. Meanwhile, Samuel grew up
        in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now Eli was very old, but he was aware of what his sons were doing
        to the people of Israel. He knew, for instance, that his sons were seducing
        the young women who assisted at the entrance of the Tabernacle.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Tent of Meeting. </b>Some manuscripts lack this entire
          sentence.
    - title: 
      content: "Eli said to them, \u201CI have been hearing reports from all the
        people about the wicked things you are doing. Why do you keep sinning? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must stop, my sons! The reports I hear among the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        people are not good. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If someone sins against another person, God[[COMMENT(0)]] can mediate
        for the guilty party. But if someone sins against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who can intercede?\u201D But Eli\u2019s sons wouldn\u2019t listen to their
        father, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was already planning to put them
        to death.  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:25 '
        content: Or <b>the judges.</b>
    - title: "A Warning for Eli\u2019s Family"
      content: 'Meanwhile, the boy Samuel grew taller and grew in favor with the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and with the people.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day a man of God came to Eli and gave him this message from the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>: \u201CI revealed myself[[COMMENT(0)]] to your
        ancestors when they were Pharaoh\u2019s slaves in Egypt. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:27 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads <b>Did I reveal myself.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'I chose your ancestor Aaron[[COMMENT(0)]] from among all the tribes
        of Israel to be my priest, to offer sacrifices on my altar, to burn incense,
        and to wear the priestly vest[[COMMENT(1)]] as he served me. And I assigned
        the sacrificial offerings to you priests. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:28a '
        content: Hebrew <b>your father.</b>
      - number: '2:28b '
        content: Hebrew <b>an ephod.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So why do you scorn my sacrifices and offerings? Why do you give
        your sons more honor than you give me\u2014for you and they have become fat
        from the best offerings of my people Israel!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel,
        says: I promised that your branch of the tribe of Levi[[COMMENT(0)]] would
        always be my priests. But I will honor those who honor me, and I will despise
        those who think lightly of me. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:30 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>that your house and your father\u2019s house.</b>"
    - title: 
      content: 'The time is coming when I will put an end to your family, so it will
        no longer serve as my priests. All the members of your family will die before
        their time. None will reach old age. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You will watch with envy as I pour out prosperity on the people of
        Israel. But no members of your family will ever live out their days. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The few not cut off from serving at my altar will survive, but only
        so their eyes can go blind and their hearts break, and their children will
        die a violent death.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '2:33 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version, which read <b>die by the
          sword; </b>Masoretic Text reads <b>die like mortals.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'And to prove that what I have said will come true, I will cause your
        two sons, Hophni and Phinehas, to die on the same day!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen I will raise up a faithful priest who will serve me and
        do what I desire. I will establish his family, and they will be priests to
        my anointed kings forever. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> Speaks to Samuel
      content: '  Meanwhile, the boy Samuel served the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        by assisting Eli. Now in those days messages from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        were very rare, and visions were quite uncommon.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One night Eli, who was almost blind by now, had gone to bed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: The lamp of God had not yet gone out, and Samuel was sleeping in the
        Tabernacle[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> near the Ark of God. </smallcaps>
      comments:
      - number: '3:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the Temple of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Suddenly the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> called out, \u201CSamuel!\u201D\u201CYes?\u201D
        Samuel replied. \u201CWhat is it?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He got up and ran to Eli. \u201CHere I am. Did you call me?\u201D\u201CI
        didn\u2019t call you,\u201D Eli replied. \u201CGo back to bed.\u201D So he
        did.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> called out again, \u201CSamuel!\u201DAgain
        Samuel got up and went to Eli. \u201CHere I am. Did you call me?\u201D\u201CI
        didn\u2019t call you, my son,\u201D Eli said. \u201CGo back to bed.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Samuel did not yet know the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> because he
        had never had a message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> before. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> called a third time, and once
        more Samuel got up and went to Eli. \u201CHere I am. Did you call me?\u201DThen
        Eli realized it was the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who was calling the boy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So he said to Samuel, \u201CGo and lie down again, and if someone
        calls again, say, \u2018Speak, <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, your servant
        is listening.\u2019\u201D So Samuel went back to bed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came and called as before, \u201CSamuel!
        Samuel!\u201DAnd Samuel replied, \u201CSpeak, your servant is listening.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Samuel, \u201CI am about
        to do a shocking thing in Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I am going to carry out all my threats against Eli and his family,
        from beginning to end. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have warned him that judgment is coming upon his family forever,
        because his sons are blaspheming God[[COMMENT(0)]] and he hasn\u2019t disciplined
        them. "
      comments:
      - number: '3:13 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>his sons have made themselves
          contemptible.</b>
    - title: Samuel Speaks for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
      content: "So I have vowed that the sins of Eli and his sons will never be forgiven
        by sacrifices or offerings.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Samuel stayed in bed until morning, then got up and opened the doors
        of the Tabernacle[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> as usual. He was afraid to tell
        Eli what the </smallcaps><smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said to him. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the house of the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "But Eli called out to him, \u201CSamuel, my son.\u201D\u201CHere
        I am,\u201D Samuel replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat did the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> say to you? Tell me
        everything. And may God strike you and even kill you if you hide anything
        from me!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Samuel told Eli everything; he didn\u2019t hold anything back.
        \u201CIt is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s will,\u201D Eli replied.
        \u201CLet him do what he thinks best.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Samuel grew up, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was with him,
        and everything Samuel said proved to be reliable. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And all Israel, from Dan in the north to Beersheba in the south,
        knew that Samuel was confirmed as a prophet of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Philistines Capture the Ark
      content: "  And Samuel\u2019s words went out to all the people of Israel.At
        that time Israel was at war with the Philistines. The Israelite army was
        camped near Ebenezer, and the Philistines were at Aphek. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Philistines attacked and defeated the army of Israel, killing
        4,000 men. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After the battle was over, the troops retreated to their camp, and
        the elders of Israel asked, \u201CWhy did the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        allow us to be defeated by the Philistines?\u201D Then they said, \u201CLet\u2019s
        bring the Ark of the Covenant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> from Shiloh.
        If we carry it into battle with us, it[[COMMENT(0)]] will save us from our
        enemies.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:3 '
        content: Or <b>he.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So they sent men to Shiloh to bring the Ark of the Covenant of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies, who is enthroned between
        the cherubim. Hophni and Phinehas, the sons of Eli, were also there with
        the Ark of the Covenant of God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When all the Israelites saw the Ark of the Covenant of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        coming into the camp, their shout of joy was so loud it made the ground shake!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat\u2019s going on?\u201D the Philistines asked. \u201CWhat\u2019s
        all the shouting about in the Hebrew camp?\u201D When they were told it was
        because the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had arrived, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "they panicked. \u201CThe gods have[[COMMENT(0)]] come into their
        camp!\u201D they cried. \u201CThis is a disaster! We have never had to face
        anything like this before! "
      comments:
      - number: '4:7 '
        content: Or <b>A god has.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Help! Who can save us from these mighty gods of Israel? They are
        the same gods who destroyed the Egyptians with plagues when Israel was in
        the wilderness. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Fight as never before, Philistines! If you don\u2019t, we will become
        the Hebrews\u2019 slaves just as they have been ours! Stand up like men and
        fight!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Philistines fought desperately, and Israel was defeated again.
        The slaughter was great; 30,000 Israelite soldiers died that day. The survivors
        turned and fled to their tents. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Death of Eli
      content: 'The Ark of God was captured, and Hophni and Phinehas, the two sons
        of Eli, were killed.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A man from the tribe of Benjamin ran from the battlefield and arrived
        at Shiloh later that same day. He had torn his clothes and put dust on his
        head to show his grief. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eli was waiting beside the road to hear the news of the battle, for
        his heart trembled for the safety of the Ark of God. When the messenger arrived
        and told what had happened, an outcry resounded throughout the town.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat is all the noise about?\u201D Eli asked.The messenger
        rushed over to Eli, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'who was ninety-eight years old and blind. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said to Eli, \u201CI have just come from the battlefield\u2014I
        was there this very day.\u201D\u201CWhat happened, my son?\u201D Eli demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIsrael has been defeated by the Philistines,\u201D the messenger
        replied. \u201CThe people have been slaughtered, and your two sons, Hophni
        and Phinehas, were also killed. And the Ark of God has been captured.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the messenger mentioned what had happened to the Ark of God,
        Eli fell backward from his seat beside the gate. He broke his neck and died,
        for he was old and overweight. He had been Israel\u2019s judge for forty
        years.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Eli\u2019s daughter-in-law, the wife of Phinehas, was pregnant and
        near her time of delivery. When she heard that the Ark of God had been captured
        and that her father-in-law and husband were dead, she went into labor and
        gave birth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She died in childbirth, but before she passed away the midwives tried
        to encourage her. \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,\u201D they said. \u201CYou
        have a baby boy!\u201D But she did not answer or pay attention to them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She named the child Ichabod (which means \u201CWhere is the glory?\u201D),
        for she said, \u201CIsrael\u2019s glory is gone.\u201D She named him this
        because the Ark of God had been captured and because her father-in-law and
        husband were dead. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Ark in Philistia
      content: '  After the Philistines captured the Ark of God, they took it from
        the battleground at Ebenezer to the town of Ashdod. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They carried the Ark of God into the temple of Dagon and placed it
        beside an idol of Dagon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the citizens of Ashdod went to see it the next morning,
        Dagon had fallen with his face to the ground in front of the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!
        So they took Dagon and put him in his place again. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the next morning the same thing happened\u2014Dagon had fallen
        face down before the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> again. This time
        his head and hands had broken off and were lying in the doorway. Only the
        trunk of his body was left intact. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That is why to this day neither the priests of Dagon nor anyone who
        enters the temple of Dagon in Ashdod will step on its threshold.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s heavy hand struck the
        people of Ashdod and the nearby villages with a plague of tumors.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:6 '
        content: Greek version and Latin Vulgate read <b>tumors; and rats appeared
          in their land, and death and destruction were throughout the city.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "When the people realized what was happening, they cried out, \u201CWe
        can\u2019t keep the Ark of the God of Israel here any longer! He is against
        us! We will all be destroyed along with Dagon, our god.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they called together the rulers of the Philistine towns and asked,
        \u201CWhat should we do with the Ark of the God of Israel?\u201DThe rulers
        discussed it and replied, \u201CMove it to the town of Gath.\u201D So they
        moved the Ark of the God of Israel to Gath. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when the Ark arrived at Gath, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        heavy hand fell on its men, young and old; he struck them with a plague of
        tumors, and there was a great panic.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they sent the Ark of God to the town of Ekron, but when the people
        of Ekron saw it coming they cried out, \u201CThey are bringing the Ark of
        the God of Israel here to kill us, too!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The people summoned the Philistine rulers again and begged them,
        \u201CPlease send the Ark of the God of Israel back to its own country, or
        it[[COMMENT(0)]] will kill us all.\u201D For the deadly plague from God had
        already begun, and great fear was sweeping across the town. "
      comments:
      - number: '5:11 '
        content: Or <b>he.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: The Philistines Return the Ark
      content: '  The Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> remained in Philistine
        territory seven months in all. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the Philistines called in their priests and diviners and asked
        them, \u201CWhat should we do about the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?
        Tell us how to return it to its own country.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSend the Ark of the God of Israel back with a gift,\u201D they
        were told. \u201CSend a guilt offering so the plague will stop. Then, if
        you are healed, you will know it was his hand that caused the plague.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat sort of guilt offering should we send?\u201D they asked.And
        they were told, \u201CSince the plague has struck both you and your five
        rulers, make five gold tumors and five gold rats, just like those that have
        ravaged your land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Make these things to show honor to the God of Israel. Perhaps then
        he will stop afflicting you, your gods, and your land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t be stubborn and rebellious as Pharaoh and the Egyptians
        were. By the time God was finished with them, they were eager to let Israel
        go.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow build a new cart, and find two cows that have just given
        birth to calves. Make sure the cows have never been yoked to a cart. Hitch
        the cows to the cart, but shut their calves away from them in a pen. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Put the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> on the cart, and beside
        it place a chest containing the gold rats and gold tumors you are sending
        as a guilt offering. Then let the cows go wherever they want. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If they cross the border of our land and go to Beth-shemesh, we will
        know it was the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who brought this great disaster
        upon us. If they don\u2019t, we will know it was not his hand that caused
        the plague. It came simply by chance.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So these instructions were carried out. Two cows were hitched to
        the cart, and their newborn calves were shut up in a pen. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and the chest containing
        the gold rats and gold tumors were placed on the cart. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And sure enough, without veering off in other directions, the cows
        went straight along the road toward Beth-shemesh, lowing as they went. The
        Philistine rulers followed them as far as the border of Beth-shemesh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The people of Beth-shemesh were harvesting wheat in the valley, and
        when they saw the Ark, they were overjoyed! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The cart came into the field of a man named Joshua and stopped beside
        a large rock. So the people broke up the wood of the cart for a fire and
        killed the cows and sacrificed them to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as
        a burnt offering. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Several men of the tribe of Levi lifted the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and the chest containing the gold rats and gold tumors from the cart and
        placed them on the large rock. Many sacrifices and burnt offerings were offered
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> that day by the people of Beth-shemesh. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The five Philistine rulers watched all this and then returned to
        Ekron that same day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The five gold tumors sent by the Philistines as a guilt offering
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> were gifts from the rulers of Ashdod,
        Gaza, Ashkelon, Gath, and Ekron. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Ark Moved to Kiriath-Jearim
      content: 'The five gold rats represented the five Philistine towns and their
        surrounding villages, which were controlled by the five rulers. The large
        rock[[COMMENT(0)]] at Beth-shemesh, where they set the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        still stands in the field of Joshua as a witness to what happened there.  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:18 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Greek version; most Hebrew manuscripts
          read <b>great meadow </b>or <b>Abel-haggedolah.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> killed seventy men[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>
        from Beth-shemesh because they looked into the Ark of the </smallcaps><smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        And the people mourned greatly because of what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had done. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:19 '
        content: As in a few Hebrew manuscripts; most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>70
          men, 50,000 men. </b>Perhaps the text should be understood to read <b>the
          <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span> killed 70 men and 50
          oxen.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho is able to stand in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        this holy God?\u201D they cried out. \u201CWhere can we send the Ark from
        here?\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: '  So the men of Kiriath-jearim came to get the Ark of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        They took it to the hillside home of Abinadab and ordained Eleazar, his son,
        to be in charge of it. '
      comments: []
    - title: Samuel Leads Israel to Victory
      content: "The Ark remained in Kiriath-jearim for a long time\u2014twenty years
        in all. During that time all Israel mourned because it seemed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had abandoned them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Samuel said to all the people of Israel, \u201CIf you want to
        return to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> with all your hearts, get rid of
        your foreign gods and your images of Ashtoreth. Turn your hearts to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and obey him alone; then he will rescue you from the Philistines.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Israelites got rid of their images of Baal and Ashtoreth and
        worshiped only the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Samuel told them, \u201CGather all of Israel to Mizpah, and
        I will pray to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they gathered at Mizpah and, in a great ceremony, drew water from
        a well and poured it out before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. They also
        went without food all day and confessed that they had sinned against the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. (It was at Mizpah that Samuel became Israel\u2019s
        judge.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the Philistine rulers heard that Israel had gathered at Mizpah,
        they mobilized their army and advanced. The Israelites were badly frightened
        when they learned that the Philistines were approaching. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t stop pleading with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        our God to save us from the Philistines!\u201D they begged Samuel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Samuel took a young lamb and offered it to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        as a whole burnt offering. He pleaded with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        to help Israel, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> answered him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Just as Samuel was sacrificing the burnt offering, the Philistines
        arrived to attack Israel. But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoke with
        a mighty voice of thunder from heaven that day, and the Philistines were
        thrown into such confusion that the Israelites defeated them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The men of Israel chased them from Mizpah to a place below Beth-car,
        slaughtering them all along the way.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Samuel then took a large stone and placed it between the towns of
        Mizpah and Jeshanah.[[COMMENT(0)]] He named it Ebenezer (which means \u201Cthe
        stone of help\u201D), for he said, \u201CUp to this point the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has helped us!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:12 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads <b>Shen.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So the Philistines were subdued and didn\u2019t invade Israel again
        for some time. And throughout Samuel\u2019s lifetime, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        powerful hand was raised against the Philistines. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Israelite villages near Ekron and Gath that the Philistines had
        captured were restored to Israel, along with the rest of the territory that
        the Philistines had taken. And there was peace between Israel and the Amorites
        in those days.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Samuel continued as Israel\u2019s judge for the rest of his life. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Each year he traveled around, setting up his court first at Bethel,
        then at Gilgal, and then at Mizpah. He judged the people of Israel at each
        of these places. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Israel Requests a King
      content: '  As Samuel grew old, he appointed his sons to be judges over Israel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joel and Abijah, his oldest sons, held court in Beersheba. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But they were not like their father, for they were greedy for money.
        They accepted bribes and perverted justice.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Finally, all the elders of Israel met at Ramah to discuss the matter
        with Samuel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLook,\u201D they told him, \u201Cyou are now old, and your
        sons are not like you. Give us a king to judge us like all the other nations
        have.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Samuel was displeased with their request and went to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        for guidance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo everything they say to you,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        replied, \u201Cfor they are rejecting me, not you. They don\u2019t want me
        to be their king any longer. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ever since I brought them from Egypt they have continually abandoned
        me and followed other gods. And now they are giving you the same treatment. '
      comments: []
    - title: Samuel Warns against a Kingdom
      content: "Do as they ask, but solemnly warn them about the way a king will
        reign over them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Samuel passed on the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s warning
        to the people who were asking him for a king. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is how a king will reign over you,\u201D Samuel said.
        \u201CThe king will draft your sons and assign them to his chariots and his
        charioteers, making them run before his chariots. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some will be generals and captains in his army,[[COMMENT(0)]] some
        will be forced to plow in his fields and harvest his crops, and some will
        make his weapons and chariot equipment. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:12 '
        content: Hebrew <b>commanders of thousands and commanders of fifties.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The king will take your daughters from you and force them to cook
        and bake and make perfumes for him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He will take away the best of your fields and vineyards and olive
        groves and give them to his own officials. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He will take a tenth of your grain and your grape harvest and distribute
        it among his officers and attendants. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He will take your male and female slaves and demand the finest of
        your cattle[[COMMENT(0)]] and donkeys for his own use. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:16 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>young men.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He will demand a tenth of your flocks, and you will be his slaves. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When that day comes, you will beg for relief from this king you are
        demanding, but then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will not help you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the people refused to listen to Samuel\u2019s warning. \u201CEven
        so, we still want a king,\u201D they said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe want to be like the nations around us. Our king will judge
        us and lead us into battle.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Samuel repeated to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> what the people
        had said, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Saul Meets Samuel
      content: '  There was a wealthy, influential man named Kish from the tribe
        of Benjamin. He was the son of Abiel, son of Zeror, son of Becorath, son
        of Aphiah, of the tribe of Benjamin. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "His son Saul was the most handsome man in Israel\u2014head and shoulders
        taller than anyone else in the land.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Kish\u2019s donkeys strayed away, and he told Saul, \u201CTake
        a servant with you, and go look for the donkeys.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Saul took one of the servants and traveled through the hill country
        of Ephraim, the land of Shalishah, the Shaalim area, and the entire land
        of Benjamin, but they couldn\u2019t find the donkeys anywhere.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, they entered the region of Zuph, and Saul said to his servant,
        \u201CLet\u2019s go home. By now my father will be more worried about us
        than about the donkeys!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the servant said, \u201CI\u2019ve just thought of something!
        There is a man of God who lives here in this town. He is held in high honor
        by all the people because everything he says comes true. Let\u2019s go find
        him. Perhaps he can tell us which way to go.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut we don\u2019t have anything to offer him,\u201D Saul replied.
        \u201CEven our food is gone, and we don\u2019t have a thing to give him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWell,\u201D the servant said, \u201CI have one small silver
        piece.[[COMMENT(0)]] We can at least offer it to the man of God and see what
        happens!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '9:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1/4 shekel of silver, </b>about 0.1 ounces or 3 grams
          in weight.
    - title: 
      content: "(In those days if people wanted a message from God, they would say,
        \u201CLet\u2019s go and ask the seer,\u201D for prophets used to be called
        seers.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Saul agreed, \u201Clet\u2019s try it!\u201D
        So they started into the town where the man of God lived.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As they were climbing the hill to the town, they met some young women
        coming out to draw water. So Saul and his servant asked, \u201CIs the seer
        here today?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D they replied. \u201CStay right on this road. He
        is at the town gates. He has just arrived to take part in a public sacrifice
        up at the place of worship. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Hurry and catch him before he goes up there to eat. The guests won\u2019t
        begin eating until he arrives to bless the food.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they entered the town, and as they passed through the gates, Samuel
        was coming out toward them to go up to the place of worship.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had told Samuel the previous
        day, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAbout this time tomorrow I will send you a man from the land
        of Benjamin. Anoint him to be the leader of my people, Israel. He will rescue
        them from the Philistines, for I have looked down on my people in mercy and
        have heard their cry.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Samuel saw Saul, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CThat\u2019s
        the man I told you about! He will rule my people.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Just then Saul approached Samuel at the gateway and asked, \u201CCan
        you please tell me where the seer\u2019s house is?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am the seer!\u201D Samuel replied. \u201CGo up to the place
        of worship ahead of me. We will eat there together, and in the morning I\u2019ll
        tell you what you want to know and send you on your way. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And don\u2019t worry about those donkeys that were lost three days
        ago, for they have been found. And I am here to tell you that you and your
        family are the focus of all Israel\u2019s hopes.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul replied, \u201CBut I\u2019m only from the tribe of Benjamin,
        the smallest tribe in Israel, and my family is the least important of all
        the families of that tribe! Why are you talking like this to me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Samuel brought Saul and his servant into the hall and placed
        them at the head of the table, honoring them above the thirty special guests. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Samuel then instructed the cook to bring Saul the finest cut of meat,
        the piece that had been set aside for the guest of honor. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the cook brought in the meat and placed it before Saul. \u201CGo
        ahead and eat it,\u201D Samuel said. \u201CI was saving it for you even before
        I invited these others!\u201D So Saul ate with Samuel that day.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they came down from the place of worship and returned to town,
        Samuel took Saul up to the roof of the house and prepared a bed for him there.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:25 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>and talked with him there.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "At daybreak the next morning, Samuel called to Saul, \u201CGet up!
        It\u2019s time you were on your way.\u201D So Saul got ready, and he and
        Samuel left the house together. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Samuel Anoints Saul as King
      content: "  Then Samuel took a flask of olive oil and poured it over Saul\u2019s
        head. He kissed Saul and said, \u201CI am doing this because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has appointed you to be the ruler over Israel, his special possession.[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        content: "Greek version reads <b>over Israel. And you will rule over the
          <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span>\u2019s people and
          save them from their enemies around them. This will be the sign to you
          that the <span class=\"ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf\">Lord</span> has appointed
          you to be leader over his special possession.</b>"
    - title: 
      content: "When you leave me today, you will see two men beside Rachel\u2019s
        tomb at Zelzah, on the border of Benjamin. They will tell you that the donkeys
        have been found and that your father has stopped worrying about them and
        is now worried about you. He is asking, \u2018Have you seen my son?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen you get to the oak of Tabor, you will see three men coming
        toward you who are on their way to worship God at Bethel. One will be bringing
        three young goats, another will have three loaves of bread, and the third
        will be carrying a wineskin full of wine. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They will greet you and offer you two of the loaves, which you are
        to accept.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen you arrive at Gibeah of God,[[COMMENT(0)]] where the garrison
        of the Philistines is located, you will meet a band of prophets coming down
        from the place of worship. They will be playing a harp, a tambourine, a flute,
        and a lyre, and they will be prophesying. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Gibeath-haelohim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'At that time the Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will come
        powerfully upon you, and you will prophesy with them. You will be changed
        into a different person. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After these signs take place, do what must be done, for God is with
        you. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Samuel\u2019s Signs Are Fulfilled"
      content: "Then go down to Gilgal ahead of me. I will join you there to sacrifice
        burnt offerings and peace offerings. You must wait for seven days until I
        arrive and give you further instructions.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As Saul turned and started to leave, God gave him a new heart, and
        all Samuel\u2019s signs were fulfilled that day. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul and his servant arrived at Gibeah, they saw a group of
        prophets coming toward them. Then the Spirit of God came powerfully upon
        Saul, and he, too, began to prophesy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When those who knew Saul heard about it, they exclaimed, \u201CWhat?
        Is even Saul a prophet? How did the son of Kish become a prophet?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And one of those standing there said, \u201CCan anyone become a prophet,
        no matter who his father is?\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]] So that is the origin of
        the saying \u201CIs even Saul a prophet?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:12 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>said, \u201CWho is their father?\u201D</b>"
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul had finished prophesying, he went up to the place of worship. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhere have you been?\u201D Saul\u2019s uncle asked him and
        his servant.\u201CWe were looking for the donkeys,\u201D Saul replied, \u201Cbut
        we couldn\u2019t find them. So we went to Samuel to ask him where they were.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COh? And what did he say?\u201D his uncle asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Saul Is Acclaimed King
      content: "\u201CHe told us that the donkeys had already been found,\u201D Saul
        replied. But Saul didn\u2019t tell his uncle what Samuel said about the kingdom.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Later Samuel called all the people of Israel to meet before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        at Mizpah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he said, \u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, has declared: I brought you from Egypt and rescued you
        from the Egyptians and from all of the nations that were oppressing you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But though I have rescued you from your misery and distress, you
        have rejected your God today and have said, \u2018No, we want a king instead!\u2019
        Now, therefore, present yourselves before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        by tribes and clans.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Samuel brought all the tribes of Israel before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        and the tribe of Benjamin was chosen by lot. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he brought each family of the tribe of Benjamin before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        and the family of the Matrites was chosen. And finally Saul son of Kish was
        chosen from among them. But when they looked for him, he had disappeared! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CWhere is he?\u201DAnd
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CHe is hiding among the baggage.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they found him and brought him out, and he stood head and shoulders
        above anyone else.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Samuel said to all the people, \u201CThis is the man the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has chosen as your king. No one in all Israel is like him!\u201DAnd all the
        people shouted, \u201CLong live the king!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Samuel told the people what the rights and duties of a king
        were. He wrote them down on a scroll and placed it before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Then Samuel sent the people home again.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul returned to his home at Gibeah, a group of men whose hearts
        God had touched went with him. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Saul Defeats the Ammonites
      content: "  About a month later,[[COMMENT(0)]] King Nahash of Ammon led his
        army against the Israelite town of Jabesh-gilead. But all the citizens of
        Jabesh asked for peace. \u201CMake a treaty with us, and we will be your
        servants,\u201D they pleaded.  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:1 '
        content: As in Dead Sea Scroll 4QSam<span class="sup">a</span> and Greek
          version; Masoretic Text lacks <b>About a month later.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Nahash said, \u201Cbut only on one condition.
        I will gouge out the right eye of every one of you as a disgrace to all Israel!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGive us seven days to send messengers throughout Israel!\u201D
        replied the elders of Jabesh. \u201CIf no one comes to save us, we will agree
        to your terms.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the messengers came to Gibeah of Saul and told the people about
        their plight, everyone broke into tears. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul had been plowing a field with his oxen, and when he returned
        to town, he asked, \u201CWhat\u2019s the matter? Why is everyone crying?\u201D
        So they told him about the message from Jabesh.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the Spirit of God came powerfully upon Saul, and he became very
        angry. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He took two oxen and cut them into pieces and sent the messengers
        to carry them throughout Israel with this message: \u201CThis is what will
        happen to the oxen of anyone who refuses to follow Saul and Samuel into battle!\u201D
        And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made the people afraid of Saul\u2019s
        anger, and all of them came out together as one. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul mobilized them at Bezek, he found that there were 300,000
        men from Israel and 30,000[[COMMENT(0)]] men from Judah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:8 '
        content: Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version read <b>70,000.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So Saul sent the messengers back to Jabesh-gilead to say, \u201CWe
        will rescue you by noontime tomorrow!\u201D There was great joy throughout
        the town when that message arrived!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The men of Jabesh then told their enemies, \u201CTomorrow we will
        come out to you, and you can do to us whatever you wish.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But before dawn the next morning, Saul arrived, having divided his
        army into three detachments. He launched a surprise attack against the Ammonites
        and slaughtered them the whole morning. The remnant of their army was so
        badly scattered that no two of them were left together.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the people exclaimed to Samuel, \u201CNow where are those men
        who said, \u2018Why should Saul rule over us?\u2019 Bring them here, and
        we will kill them!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Saul replied, \u201CNo one will be executed today, for today
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has rescued Israel!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Samuel said to the people, \u201CCome, let us all go to Gilgal
        to renew the kingdom.\u201D "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Samuel\u2019s Farewell Address"
      content: "  Then Samuel addressed all Israel: \u201CI have done as you asked
        and given you a king. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Your king is now your leader. I stand here before you\u2014an old,
        gray-haired man\u2014and my sons serve you. I have served as your leader
        from the time I was a boy to this very day. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now testify against me in the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and before his anointed one. Whose ox or donkey have I stolen? Have I ever
        cheated any of you? Have I ever oppressed you? Have I ever taken a bribe
        and perverted justice? Tell me and I will make right whatever I have done
        wrong.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo,\u201D they replied, \u201Cyou have never cheated or oppressed
        us, and you have never taken even a single bribe.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and his anointed one are my
        witnesses today,\u201D Samuel declared, \u201Cthat my hands are clean.\u201D\u201CYes,
        he is a witness,\u201D they replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt was the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who appointed Moses
        and Aaron,\u201D Samuel continued. \u201CHe brought your ancestors out of
        the land of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now stand here quietly before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> as
        I remind you of all the great things the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has
        done for you and your ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen the Israelites were[[COMMENT(0)]] in Egypt and cried out
        to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, he sent Moses and Aaron to rescue them
        from Egypt and to bring them into this land. "
      comments:
      - number: '12:8 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>When Jacob was. </b>The names \u201CJacob\u201D and \u201CIsrael\u201D
          are often interchanged throughout the Old Testament, referring sometimes
          to the individual patriarch and sometimes to the nation."
    - title: 
      content: "But the people soon forgot about the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        their God, so he handed them over to Sisera, the commander of Hazor\u2019s
        army, and also to the Philistines and to the king of Moab, who fought against
        them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen they cried to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> again and
        confessed, \u2018We have sinned by turning away from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and worshiping the images of Baal and Ashtoreth. But we will worship you
        and you alone if you will rescue us from our enemies.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent Gideon,[[COMMENT(0)]] Bedan,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        Jephthah, and Samuel[[COMMENT(2)]] to save you, and you lived in safety.  '
      comments:
      - number: '12:11a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Jerub-baal, </b>another name for Gideon; see Judg 6:32.
      - number: '12:11b '
        content: Greek and Syriac versions read <b>Barak.</b>
      - number: '12:11c '
        content: Greek and Syriac versions read <b>Samson.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut when you were afraid of Nahash, the king of Ammon, you
        came to me and said that you wanted a king to reign over you, even though
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God was already your king. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All right, here is the king you have chosen. You asked for him, and
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has granted your request.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow if you fear and worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and listen to his voice, and if you do not rebel against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        commands, then both you and your king will show that you recognize the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        as your God. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if you rebel against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s commands
        and refuse to listen to him, then his hand will be as heavy upon you as it
        was upon your ancestors.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow stand here and see the great thing the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is about to do. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You know that it does not rain at this time of the year during the
        wheat harvest. I will ask the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> to send thunder
        and rain today. Then you will realize how wicked you have been in asking
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for a king!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Samuel called to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        sent thunder and rain that day. And all the people were terrified of the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and of Samuel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPray to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God for us, or
        we will die!\u201D they all said to Samuel. \u201CFor now we have added to
        our sins by asking for a king.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,\u201D Samuel reassured them. \u201CYou
        have certainly done wrong, but make sure now that you worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        with all your heart, and don\u2019t turn your back on him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t go back to worshiping worthless idols that cannot help
        or rescue you\u2014they are totally useless! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will not abandon his people, because
        that would dishonor his great name. For it has pleased the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        to make you his very own people.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAs for me, I will certainly not sin against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        by ending my prayers for you. And I will continue to teach you what is good
        and right. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But be sure to fear the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> and faithfully
        serve him. Think of all the wonderful things he has done for you. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Continued War with Philistia
      content: '  Saul was thirty[[COMMENT(0)]] years old when he became king, and
        he reigned for forty-two years.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '13:1a '
        content: As in a few Greek manuscripts; the number is missing in the Hebrew.
      - number: '13:1b '
        content: Hebrew <b>reigned . . . and two; </b>the number is incomplete in
          the Hebrew. Compare Acts 13:21.
    - title: 
      content: "Saul selected 3,000 special troops from the army of Israel and sent
        the rest of the men home. He took 2,000 of the chosen men with him to Micmash
        and the hill country of Bethel. The other 1,000 went with Saul\u2019s son
        Jonathan to Gibeah in the land of Benjamin.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon after this, Jonathan attacked and defeated the garrison of Philistines
        at Geba. The news spread quickly among the Philistines. So Saul blew the
        ram\u2019s horn throughout the land, saying, \u201CHebrews, hear this! Rise
        up in revolt!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All Israel heard the news that Saul had destroyed the Philistine
        garrison at Geba and that the Philistines now hated the Israelites more than
        ever. So the entire Israelite army was summoned to join Saul at Gilgal.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Philistines mustered a mighty army of 3,000[[COMMENT(0)]] chariots,
        6,000 charioteers, and as many warriors as the grains of sand on the seashore!
        They camped at Micmash east of Beth-aven. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:5 '
        content: As in Greek and Syriac versions; Hebrew reads <b>30,000.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The men of Israel saw what a tight spot they were in; and because
        they were hard pressed by the enemy, they tried to hide in caves, thickets,
        rocks, holes, and cisterns. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Saul\u2019s Disobedience and Samuel\u2019s Rebuke"
      content: 'Some of them crossed the Jordan River and escaped into the land of
        Gad and Gilead.Meanwhile, Saul stayed at Gilgal, and his men were trembling
        with fear. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul waited there seven days for Samuel, as Samuel had instructed
        him earlier, but Samuel still didn\u2019t come. Saul realized that his troops
        were rapidly slipping away. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So he demanded, \u201CBring me the burnt offering and the peace offerings!\u201D
        And Saul sacrificed the burnt offering himself.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Just as Saul was finishing with the burnt offering, Samuel arrived.
        Saul went out to meet and welcome him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "but Samuel said, \u201CWhat is this you have done?\u201DSaul replied,
        \u201CI saw my men scattering from me, and you didn\u2019t arrive when you
        said you would, and the Philistines are at Micmash ready for battle. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So I said, \u2018The Philistines are ready to march against us at
        Gilgal, and I haven\u2019t even asked for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        help!\u2019 So I felt compelled to offer the burnt offering myself before
        you came.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHow foolish!\u201D Samuel exclaimed. \u201CYou have not kept
        the command the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God gave you. Had you kept
        it, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> would have established your kingdom over
        Israel forever. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Israel\u2019s Military Disadvantage"
      content: "But now your kingdom must end, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has sought out a man after his own heart. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has already appointed him to be the leader of his people, because you have
        not kept the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Samuel then left Gilgal and went on his way, but the rest of the
        troops went with Saul to meet the army. They went up from Gilgal to Gibeah
        in the land of Benjamin.[[COMMENT(0)]] When Saul counted the men who were
        still with him, he found only 600 were left! '
      comments:
      - number: '13:15 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>Samuel then left Gilgal and
          went to Gibeah in the land of Benjamin.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul and Jonathan and the troops with them were staying at Geba in
        the land of Benjamin. The Philistines set up their camp at Micmash. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Three raiding parties soon left the camp of the Philistines. One
        went north toward Ophrah in the land of Shual, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'another went west to Beth-horon, and the third moved toward the border
        above the valley of Zeboim near the wilderness.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There were no blacksmiths in the land of Israel in those days. The
        Philistines wouldn\u2019t allow them for fear they would make swords and
        spears for the Hebrews. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So whenever the Israelites needed to sharpen their plowshares, picks,
        axes, or sickles,[[COMMENT(0)]] they had to take them to a Philistine blacksmith. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:20 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>or plowshares.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The charges were as follows: a quarter of an ounce[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of silver for sharpening a plowshare or a pick, and an eighth of an ounce[[COMMENT(1)]]
        for sharpening an ax or making the point of an ox goad. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:21a '
        content: Hebrew <b>1 pim </b>[8 grams].
      - number: '13:21b '
        content: Hebrew <b>1/3 [of a shekel] </b>[4 grams].
    - title: 
      content: 'So on the day of the battle none of the people of Israel had a sword
        or spear, except for Saul and Jonathan.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Jonathan\u2019s Daring Plan"
      content: "  One day Jonathan said to his armor bearer, \u201CCome on, let\u2019s
        go over to where the Philistines have their outpost.\u201D But Jonathan did
        not tell his father what he was doing.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, Saul and his 600 men were camped on the outskirts of Gibeah,
        around the pomegranate tree[[COMMENT(0)]] at Migron. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:2 '
        content: Or <b>around the rock of Rimmon; </b>compare Judg 20:45, 47; 21:13.
    - title: 
      content: "Among Saul\u2019s men was Ahijah the priest, who was wearing the
        ephod, the priestly vest. Ahijah was the son of Ichabod\u2019s brother Ahitub,
        son of Phinehas, son of Eli, the priest of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        who had served at Shiloh.No one realized that Jonathan had left the Israelite
        camp. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'To reach the Philistine outpost, Jonathan had to go down between
        two rocky cliffs that were called Bozez and Seneh. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The cliff on the north was in front of Micmash, and the one on the
        south was in front of Geba. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLet\u2019s go across to the outpost of those pagans,\u201D
        Jonathan said to his armor bearer. \u201CPerhaps the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will help us, for nothing can hinder the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. He
        can win a battle whether he has many warriors or only a few!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo what you think is best,\u201D the armor bearer replied.
        \u201CI\u2019m with you completely, whatever you decide.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right, then,\u201D Jonathan told him. \u201CWe will cross
        over and let them see us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If they say to us, \u2018Stay where you are or we\u2019ll kill you,\u2019
        then we will stop and not go up to them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if they say, \u2018Come on up and fight,\u2019 then we will go
        up. That will be the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s sign that he will
        help us defeat them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the Philistines saw them coming, they shouted, \u201CLook! The
        Hebrews are crawling out of their holes!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the men from the outpost shouted to Jonathan, \u201CCome on
        up here, and we\u2019ll teach you a lesson!\u201D\u201CCome on, climb right
        behind me,\u201D Jonathan said to his armor bearer, \u201Cfor the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will help us defeat them!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they climbed up using both hands and feet, and the Philistines
        fell before Jonathan, and his armor bearer killed those who came behind them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They killed some twenty men in all, and their bodies were scattered
        over about half an acre.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '14:14 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>half a yoke; </b>a \u201Cyoke\u201D was the amount of
          land plowed by a pair of yoked oxen in one day."
    - title: Israel Defeats the Philistines
      content: 'Suddenly, panic broke out in the Philistine army, both in the camp
        and in the field, including even the outposts and raiding parties. And just
        then an earthquake struck, and everyone was terrified.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul\u2019s lookouts in Gibeah of Benjamin saw a strange sight\u2014the
        vast army of Philistines began to melt away in every direction.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:16 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>they went and there.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCall the roll and find out who\u2019s missing,\u201D Saul ordered.
        And when they checked, they found that Jonathan and his armor bearer were
        gone.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul shouted to Ahijah, \u201CBring the ephod here!\u201D For
        at that time Ahijah was wearing the ephod in front of the Israelites.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:18 '
        content: "As in some Greek manuscripts; Hebrew reads <b>\u201CBring the Ark
          of God.\u201D For at that time the Ark of God was with the Israelites.</b>"
    - title: 
      content: "But while Saul was talking to the priest, the confusion in the Philistine
        camp grew louder and louder. So Saul said to the priest, \u201CNever mind;
        let\u2019s get going!\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Withdraw your hand.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Saul and all his men rushed out to the battle and found the
        Philistines killing each other. There was terrible confusion everywhere. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Even the Hebrews who had previously gone over to the Philistine army
        revolted and joined in with Saul, Jonathan, and the rest of the Israelites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Likewise, the men of Israel who were hiding in the hill country of
        Ephraim joined the chase when they saw the Philistines running away. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Saul\u2019s Foolish Oath"
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> saved Israel that day, and the
        battle continued to rage even beyond Beth-aven.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now the men of Israel were pressed to exhaustion that day, because
        Saul had placed them under an oath, saying, \u201CLet a curse fall on anyone
        who eats before evening\u2014before I have full revenge on my enemies.\u201D
        So no one ate anything all day, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'even though they had all found honeycomb on the ground in the forest. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They didn\u2019t dare touch the honey because they all feared the
        oath they had taken.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Jonathan had not heard his father\u2019s command, and he dipped
        the end of his stick into a piece of honeycomb and ate the honey. After he
        had eaten it, he felt refreshed.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:27 '
        content: Or <b>his eyes brightened; </b>similarly in 14:29.
    - title: 
      content: "But one of the men saw him and said, \u201CYour father made the army
        take a strict oath that anyone who eats food today will be cursed. That is
        why everyone is weary and faint.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMy father has made trouble for us all!\u201D Jonathan exclaimed.
        \u201CA command like that only hurts us. See how refreshed I am now that
        I have eaten this little bit of honey. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If the men had been allowed to eat freely from the food they found
        among our enemies, think how many more Philistines we could have killed!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They chased and killed the Philistines all day from Micmash to Aijalon,
        growing more and more faint. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'That evening they rushed for the battle plunder and butchered the
        sheep, goats, cattle, and calves, but they ate them without draining the
        blood. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Someone reported to Saul, \u201CLook, the men are sinning against
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by eating meat that still has blood in it.\u201D\u201CThat
        is very wrong,\u201D Saul said. \u201CFind a large stone and roll it over
        here. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then go out among the troops and tell them, \u2018Bring the cattle,
        sheep, and goats here to me. Kill them here, and drain the blood before you
        eat them. Do not sin against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by eating meat
        with the blood still in it.\u2019\u201DSo that night all the troops brought
        their animals and slaughtered them there. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Saul built an altar to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>; it was
        the first of the altars he built to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul said, \u201CLet\u2019s chase the Philistines all night
        and plunder them until sunrise. Let\u2019s destroy every last one of them.\u201DHis
        men replied, \u201CWe\u2019ll do whatever you think is best.\u201DBut the
        priest said, \u201CLet\u2019s ask God first.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Saul asked God, \u201CShould we go after the Philistines? Will
        you help us defeat them?\u201D But God made no reply that day.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul said to the leaders, \u201CSomething\u2019s wrong! I want
        all my army commanders to come here. We must find out what sin was committed
        today. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I vow by the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who rescued
        Israel that the sinner will surely die, even if it is my own son Jonathan!\u201D
        But no one would tell him what the trouble was.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul said, \u201CJonathan and I will stand over here, and all
        of you stand over there.\u201DAnd the people responded to Saul, \u201CWhatever
        you think is best.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel,
        please show us who is guilty and who is innocent.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D Then
        they cast sacred lots, and Jonathan and Saul were chosen as the guilty ones,
        and the people were declared innocent.  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:41 '
        content: Greek version adds <b>If the fault is with me or my son Jonathan,
          respond with Urim; but if the men of Israel are at fault, respond with
          Thummim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul said, \u201CNow cast lots again and choose between me and
        Jonathan.\u201D And Jonathan was shown to be the guilty one.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTell me what you have done,\u201D Saul demanded of Jonathan.\u201CI
        tasted a little honey,\u201D Jonathan admitted. \u201CIt was only a little
        bit on the end of my stick. Does that deserve death?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes, Jonathan,\u201D Saul said, \u201Cyou must die! May God
        strike me and even kill me if you do not die for this.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the people broke in and said to Saul, \u201CJonathan has won
        this great victory for Israel. Should he die? Far from it! As surely as the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives, not one hair on his head will be touched,
        for God helped him do a great deed today.\u201D So the people rescued Jonathan,
        and he was not put to death.  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Saul\u2019s Military Successes"
      content: 'Then Saul called back the army from chasing the Philistines, and
        the Philistines returned home.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now when Saul had secured his grasp on Israel\u2019s throne, he fought
        against his enemies in every direction\u2014against Moab, Ammon, Edom, the
        kings of Zobah, and the Philistines. And wherever he turned, he was victorious.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '14:47 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>he acted wickedly.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He performed great deeds and conquered the Amalekites, saving Israel
        from all those who had plundered them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul\u2019s sons included Jonathan, Ishbosheth,[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        Malkishua. He also had two daughters: Merab, who was older, and Michal. "
      comments:
      - number: '14:49 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Ishvi, </b>a variant name for Ishbosheth; also known as
          Esh-baal.
    - title: 
      content: "Saul\u2019s wife was Ahinoam, the daughter of Ahimaaz. The commander
        of Saul\u2019s army was Abner, the son of Saul\u2019s uncle Ner. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul\u2019s father, Kish, and Abner\u2019s father, Ner, were both
        sons of Abiel.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Saul Defeats the Amalekites
      content: "  One day Samuel said to Saul, \u201CIt was the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        who told me to anoint you as king of his people, Israel. Now listen to this
        message from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> of Heaven\u2019s Armies
        has declared: I have decided to settle accounts with the nation of Amalek
        for opposing Israel when they came from Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now go and completely destroy[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps> the entire
        Amalekite nation\u2014men, women, children, babies, cattle, sheep, goats,
        camels, and donkeys.\u201D</smallcaps>  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:3 '
        content: The Hebrew term used here refers to the complete consecration of
          things or people to the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>,
          either by destroying them or by giving them as an offering; also in 15:8,
          9, 15, 18, 20, 21.
    - title: 
      content: 'So Saul mobilized his army at Telaim. There were 200,000 soldiers
        from Israel and 10,000 men from Judah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Saul and his army went to a town of the Amalekites and lay in
        wait in the valley. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul sent this warning to the Kenites: \u201CMove away from where
        the Amalekites live, or you will die with them. For you showed kindness to
        all the people of Israel when they came up from Egypt.\u201D So the Kenites
        packed up and left.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Saul slaughtered the Amalekites from Havilah all the way to
        Shur, east of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He captured Agag, the Amalekite king, but completely destroyed everyone
        else. '
      comments: []
    - title: The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> Rejects Saul
      content: "Saul and his men spared Agag\u2019s life and kept the best of the
        sheep and goats, the cattle, the fat calves, and the lambs\u2014everything,
        in fact, that appealed to them. They destroyed only what was worthless or
        of poor quality.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Samuel, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am sorry that I ever made Saul king, for he has not been
        loyal to me and has refused to obey my command.\u201D Samuel was so deeply
        moved when he heard this that he cried out to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        all night.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Early the next morning Samuel went to find Saul. Someone told him,
        \u201CSaul went to the town of Carmel to set up a monument to himself; then
        he went on to Gilgal.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Samuel finally found him, Saul greeted him cheerfully. \u201CMay
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> bless you,\u201D he said. \u201CI have carried
        out the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen what is all the bleating of sheep and goats and the lowing
        of cattle I hear?\u201D Samuel demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt\u2019s true that the army spared the best of the sheep,
        goats, and cattle,\u201D Saul admitted. \u201CBut they are going to sacrifice
        them to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God. We have destroyed everything
        else.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Samuel said to Saul, \u201CStop! Listen to what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told me last night!\u201D\u201CWhat did he tell you?\u201D Saul asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Samuel told him, \u201CAlthough you may think little of yourself,
        are you not the leader of the tribes of Israel? The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has anointed you king of Israel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent you on a mission and told
        you, \u2018Go and completely destroy the sinners, the Amalekites, until they
        are all dead.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why haven\u2019t you obeyed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>? Why
        did you rush for the plunder and do what was evil in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut I did obey the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,\u201D Saul
        insisted. \u201CI carried out the mission he gave me. I brought back King
        Agag, but I destroyed everyone else. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then my troops brought in the best of the sheep, goats, cattle, and
        plunder to sacrifice to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God in Gilgal.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Samuel replied,\u201CWhat is more pleasing to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>:your
        burnt offerings and sacrificesor your obedience to his voice?Listen! Obedience
        is better than sacrifice,and submission is better than offering the fat of
        rams.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Saul Pleads for Forgiveness
      content: "Rebellion is as sinful as witchcraft,and stubbornness as bad as worshiping
        idols.So because you have rejected the command of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,he
        has rejected you as king.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul admitted to Samuel, \u201CYes, I have sinned. I have disobeyed
        your instructions and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command, for
        I was afraid of the people and did what they demanded. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now, please forgive my sin and come back with me so that I may
        worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Samuel replied, \u201CI will not go back with you! Since you
        have rejected the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s command, he has rejected
        you as king of Israel.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Samuel turned to go, Saul tried to hold him back and tore the
        hem of his robe. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Samuel said to him, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has
        torn the kingdom of Israel from you today and has given it to someone else\u2014one
        who is better than you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he who is the Glory of Israel will not lie, nor will he change
        his mind, for he is not human that he should change his mind!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul pleaded again, \u201CI know I have sinned. But please,
        at least honor me before the elders of my people and before Israel by coming
        back with me so that I may worship the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: Samuel Executes King Agag
      content: 'So Samuel finally agreed and went back with him, and Saul worshiped
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Samuel said, \u201CBring King Agag to me.\u201D Agag arrived
        full of hope, for he thought, \u201CSurely the worst is over, and I have
        been spared!\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '15:32 '
        content: "Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version read <b>Agag arrived hesitantly,
          for he thought, \u201CSurely this is the bitterness of death.\u201D</b>"
    - title: 
      content: "But Samuel said, \u201CAs your sword has killed the sons of many
        mothers, now your mother will be childless.\u201D And Samuel cut Agag to
        pieces before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> at Gilgal.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Samuel went home to Ramah, and Saul returned to his house at
        Gibeah of Saul. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Samuel Anoints David as King
      content: "  Now the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Samuel, \u201CYou have
        mourned long enough for Saul. I have rejected him as king of Israel, so fill
        your flask with olive oil and go to Bethlehem. Find a man named Jesse who
        lives there, for I have selected one of his sons to be my king.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Samuel asked, \u201CHow can I do that? If Saul hears about it,
        he will kill me.\u201D\u201CTake a heifer with you,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        replied, \u201Cand say that you have come to make a sacrifice to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Invite Jesse to the sacrifice, and I will show you which of his sons
        to anoint for me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Samuel did as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> instructed. When
        he arrived at Bethlehem, the elders of the town came trembling to meet him.
        \u201CWhat\u2019s wrong?\u201D they asked. \u201CDo you come in peace?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D Samuel replied. \u201CI have come to sacrifice to
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. Purify yourselves and come with me to the
        sacrifice.\u201D Then Samuel performed the purification rite for Jesse and
        his sons and invited them to the sacrifice, too.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they arrived, Samuel took one look at Eliab and thought, \u201CSurely
        this is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anointed!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Samuel, \u201CDon\u2019t
        judge by his appearance or height, for I have rejected him. The <smallcaps>Lord
        </smallcaps>doesn\u2019t see things the way you see them. People judge by
        outward appearance, but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> looks at the heart.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jesse told his son Abinadab to step forward and walk in front
        of Samuel. But Samuel said, \u201CThis is not the one the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has chosen.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Next Jesse summoned Shimea,[[COMMENT(0)]] but Samuel said, \u201CNeither
        is this the one the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has chosen.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '16:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shammah, </b>a variant spelling of Shimea; compare 1 Chr
          2:13; 20:7.
    - title: 
      content: "In the same way all seven of Jesse\u2019s sons were presented to
        Samuel. But Samuel said to Jesse, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has
        not chosen any of these.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Samuel asked, \u201CAre these all the sons you have?\u201D\u201CThere
        is still the youngest,\u201D Jesse replied. \u201CBut he\u2019s out in the
        fields watching the sheep and goats.\u201D\u201CSend for him at once,\u201D
        Samuel said. \u201CWe will not sit down to eat until he arrives.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jesse sent for him. He was dark and handsome, with beautiful eyes.And
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CThis is the one; anoint him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "David Serves in Saul\u2019s Court"
      content: 'So as David stood there among his brothers, Samuel took the flask
        of olive oil he had brought and anointed David with the oil. And the Spirit
        of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came powerfully upon David from that day
        on. Then Samuel returned to Ramah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now the Spirit of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had left Saul,
        and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent a tormenting spirit[[COMMENT(0)]]
        that filled him with depression and fear.  '
      comments:
      - number: '16:14 '
        content: Or <b>an evil spirit; </b>also in 16:15, 16, 23.
    - title: 
      content: "Some of Saul\u2019s servants said to him, \u201CA tormenting spirit
        from God is troubling you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let us find a good musician to play the harp whenever the tormenting
        spirit troubles you. He will play soothing music, and you will soon be well
        again.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Saul said. \u201CFind me someone who plays
        well, and bring him here.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One of the servants said to Saul, \u201COne of Jesse\u2019s sons
        from Bethlehem is a talented harp player. Not only that\u2014he is a brave
        warrior, a man of war, and has good judgment. He is also a fine-looking young
        man, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is with him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Saul sent messengers to Jesse to say, \u201CSend me your son David,
        the shepherd.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jesse responded by sending David to Saul, along with a young goat,
        a donkey loaded with bread, and a wineskin full of wine.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David went to Saul and began serving him. Saul loved David very
        much, and David became his armor bearer.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul sent word to Jesse asking, \u201CPlease let David remain
        in my service, for I am very pleased with him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Goliath Challenges the Israelites
      content: '  The Philistines now mustered their army for battle and camped between
        Socoh in Judah and Azekah at Ephes-dammim. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul countered by gathering his Israelite troops near the valley
        of Elah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the Philistines and Israelites faced each other on opposite hills,
        with the valley between them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Goliath, a Philistine champion from Gath, came out of the Philistine
        ranks to face the forces of Israel. He was over nine feet[[COMMENT(0)]] tall! '
      comments:
      - number: '17:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>6 cubits and 1 span </b>[which totals about 9.75 feet
          or 3 meters]; Dead Sea Scrolls and Greek version read <b>4 cubits and 1
          span </b>[which totals about 6.75 feet or 2 meters].
    - title: 
      content: 'He wore a bronze helmet, and his bronze coat of mail weighed 125
        pounds.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '17:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5,000 shekels </b>[57 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: 'He also wore bronze leg armor, and he carried a bronze javelin on
        his shoulder. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The shaft of his spear was as heavy and thick as a weaver\u2019s
        beam, tipped with an iron spearhead that weighed 15 pounds.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        His armor bearer walked ahead of him carrying a shield.  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>600 shekels </b>[6.8 kilograms].
    - title: 
      content: "Goliath stood and shouted a taunt across to the Israelites. \u201CWhy
        are you all coming out to fight?\u201D he called. \u201CI am the Philistine
        champion, but you are only the servants of Saul. Choose one man to come down
        here and fight me! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If he kills me, then we will be your slaves. But if I kill him, you
        will be our slaves! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I defy the armies of Israel today! Send me a man who will fight me!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: "Jesse Sends David to Saul\u2019s Camp"
      content: 'When Saul and the Israelites heard this, they were terrified and
        deeply shaken.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now David was the son of a man named Jesse, an Ephrathite from Bethlehem
        in the land of Judah. Jesse was an old man at that time, and he had eight
        sons. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jesse\u2019s three oldest sons\u2014Eliab, Abinadab, and Shimea[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014had
        already joined Saul\u2019s army to fight the Philistines. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shammah, </b>a variant spelling of Shimea; compare 1 Chr
          2:13; 20:7.
    - title: 
      content: "David was the youngest son. David\u2019s three oldest brothers stayed
        with Saul\u2019s army, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but David went back and forth so he could help his father with the
        sheep in Bethlehem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For forty days, every morning and evening, the Philistine champion
        strutted in front of the Israelite army.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Jesse said to David, \u201CTake this basket[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of roasted grain and these ten loaves of bread, and carry them quickly to
        your brothers. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>ephah </b>[20 quarts or 22 liters].
    - title: 
      content: "And give these ten cuts of cheese to their captain. See how your
        brothers are getting along, and bring back a report on how they are doing.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '17:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>and take their pledge.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "David\u2019s brothers were with Saul and the Israelite army at the
        valley of Elah, fighting against the Philistines.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David left the sheep with another shepherd and set out early the
        next morning with the gifts, as Jesse had directed him. He arrived at the
        camp just as the Israelite army was leaving for the battlefield with shouts
        and battle cries. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Soon the Israelite and Philistine forces stood facing each other,
        army against army. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David left his things with the keeper of supplies and hurried out
        to the ranks to greet his brothers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As he was talking with them, Goliath, the Philistine champion from
        Gath, came out from the Philistine ranks. Then David heard him shout his
        usual taunt to the army of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as the Israelite army saw him, they began to run away in
        fright. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHave you seen the giant?\u201D the men asked. \u201CHe comes
        out each day to defy Israel. The king has offered a huge reward to anyone
        who kills him. He will give that man one of his daughters for a wife, and
        the man\u2019s entire family will be exempted from paying taxes!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David asked the soldiers standing nearby, \u201CWhat will a man get
        for killing this Philistine and ending his defiance of Israel? Who is this
        pagan Philistine anyway, that he is allowed to defy the armies of the living
        God?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And these men gave David the same reply. They said, \u201CYes, that
        is the reward for killing him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when David\u2019s oldest brother, Eliab, heard David talking
        to the men, he was angry. \u201CWhat are you doing around here anyway?\u201D
        he demanded. \u201CWhat about those few sheep you\u2019re supposed to be
        taking care of? I know about your pride and deceit. You just want to see
        the battle!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat have I done now?\u201D David replied. \u201CI was only
        asking a question!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He walked over to some others and asked them the same thing and received
        the same answer. '
      comments: []
    - title: David Kills Goliath
      content: "Then David\u2019s question was reported to King Saul, and the king
        sent for him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t worry about this Philistine,\u201D David told Saul.
        \u201CI\u2019ll go fight him!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be ridiculous!\u201D Saul replied. \u201CThere\u2019s
        no way you can fight this Philistine and possibly win! You\u2019re only a
        boy, and he\u2019s been a man of war since his youth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But David persisted. \u201CI have been taking care of my father\u2019s
        sheep and goats,\u201D he said. \u201CWhen a lion or a bear comes to steal
        a lamb from the flock, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I go after it with a club and rescue the lamb from its mouth. If
        the animal turns on me, I catch it by the jaw and club it to death. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have done this to both lions and bears, and I\u2019ll do it to
        this pagan Philistine, too, for he has defied the armies of the living God! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> who rescued me from the claws of
        the lion and the bear will rescue me from this Philistine!\u201DSaul finally
        consented. \u201CAll right, go ahead,\u201D he said. \u201CAnd may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        be with you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul gave David his own armor\u2014a bronze helmet and a coat
        of mail. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David put it on, strapped the sword over it, and took a step or two
        to see what it was like, for he had never worn such things before.\u201CI
        can\u2019t go in these,\u201D he protested to Saul. \u201CI\u2019m not used
        to them.\u201D So David took them off again. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He picked up five smooth stones from a stream and put them into his
        shepherd\u2019s bag. Then, armed only with his shepherd\u2019s staff and
        sling, he started across the valley to fight the Philistine.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Goliath walked out toward David with his shield bearer ahead of him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'sneering in contempt at this ruddy-faced boy. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAm I a dog,\u201D he roared at David, \u201Cthat you come at
        me with a stick?\u201D And he cursed David by the names of his gods. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCome over here, and I\u2019ll give your flesh to the birds
        and wild animals!\u201D Goliath yelled.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David replied to the Philistine, \u201CYou come to me with sword,
        spear, and javelin, but I come to you in the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        of Heaven\u2019s Armies\u2014the God of the armies of Israel, whom you have
        defied. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Today the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will conquer you, and I will
        kill you and cut off your head. And then I will give the dead bodies of your
        men to the birds and wild animals, and the whole world will know that there
        is a God in Israel! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And everyone assembled here will know that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        rescues his people, but not with sword and spear. This is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        battle, and he will give you to us!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As Goliath moved closer to attack, David quickly ran out to meet
        him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Reaching into his shepherd\u2019s bag and taking out a stone, he
        hurled it with his sling and hit the Philistine in the forehead. The stone
        sank in, and Goliath stumbled and fell face down on the ground.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David triumphed over the Philistine with only a sling and a stone,
        for he had no sword. '
      comments: []
    - title: Israel Routs the Philistines
      content: "Then David ran over and pulled Goliath\u2019s sword from its sheath.
        David used it to kill him and cut off his head.When the Philistines saw that
        their champion was dead, they turned and ran. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the men of Israel and Judah gave a great shout of triumph and
        rushed after the Philistines, chasing them as far as Gath[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        the gates of Ekron. The bodies of the dead and wounded Philistines were strewn
        all along the road from Shaaraim, as far as Gath and Ekron. '
      comments:
      - number: '17:52 '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts; Hebrew reads <b>a valley.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the Israelite army returned and plundered the deserted Philistine
        camp. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "(David took the Philistine\u2019s head to Jerusalem, but he stored
        the man\u2019s armor in his own tent.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As Saul watched David go out to fight the Philistine, he asked Abner,
        the commander of his army, \u201CAbner, whose son is this young man?\u201D\u201CI
        really don\u2019t know,\u201D Abner declared.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWell, find out who he is!\u201D the king told him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As soon as David returned from killing Goliath, Abner brought him
        to Saul with the Philistine\u2019s head still in his hand. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Saul Becomes Jealous of David
      content: "  After David had finished talking with Saul, he met Jonathan, the
        king\u2019s son. There was an immediate bond between them, for Jonathan loved
        David. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From that day on Saul kept David with him and wouldn\u2019t let him
        return home. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And Jonathan made a solemn pact with David, because he loved him
        as he loved himself. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jonathan sealed the pact by taking off his robe and giving it to
        David, together with his tunic, sword, bow, and belt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Whatever Saul asked David to do, David did it successfully. So Saul
        made him a commander over the men of war, an appointment that was welcomed
        by the people and Saul\u2019s officers alike.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the victorious Israelite army was returning home after David
        had killed the Philistine, women from all the towns of Israel came out to
        meet King Saul. They sang and danced for joy with tambourines and cymbals.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:6 '
        content: The type of instrument represented by the word <b>cymbals </b>is
          uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "This was their song:\u201CSaul has killed his thousands,and David
        his ten thousands!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This made Saul very angry. \u201CWhat\u2019s this?\u201D he said.
        \u201CThey credit David with ten thousands and me with only thousands. Next
        they\u2019ll be making him their king!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So from that time on Saul kept a jealous eye on David.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The very next day a tormenting spirit[[COMMENT(0)]] from God overwhelmed
        Saul, and he began to rave in his house like a madman. David was playing
        the harp, as he did each day. But Saul had a spear in his hand, '
      comments:
      - number: '18:10 '
        content: Or <b>an evil spirit.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'and he suddenly hurled it at David, intending to pin him to the wall.
        But David escaped him twice.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul was then afraid of David, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        was with David and had turned away from Saul. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Finally, Saul sent him away and appointed him commander over 1,000
        men, and David faithfully led his troops into battle.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David continued to succeed in everything he did, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        was with him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul recognized this, he became even more afraid of him. '
      comments: []
    - title: "David Marries Saul\u2019s Daughter"
      content: 'But all Israel and Judah loved David because he was so successful
        at leading his troops into battle.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Saul said to David, \u201CI am ready to give you my older
        daughter, Merab, as your wife. But first you must prove yourself to be a
        real warrior by fighting the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s battles.\u201D
        For Saul thought, \u201CI\u2019ll send him out against the Philistines and
        let them kill him rather than doing it myself.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho am I, and what is my family in Israel that I should be
        the king\u2019s son-in-law?\u201D David exclaimed. \u201CMy father\u2019s
        family is nothing!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So[[COMMENT(0)]] when the time came for Saul to give his daughter
        Merab in marriage to David, he gave her instead to Adriel, a man from Meholah.  '
      comments:
      - number: '18:19 '
        content: Or <b>But.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "In the meantime, Saul\u2019s daughter Michal had fallen in love with
        David, and Saul was delighted when he heard about it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHere\u2019s another chance to see him killed by the Philistines!\u201D
        Saul said to himself. But to David he said, \u201CToday you have a second
        chance to become my son-in-law!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul told his men to say to David, \u201CThe king really likes
        you, and so do we. Why don\u2019t you accept the king\u2019s offer and become
        his son-in-law?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Saul\u2019s men said these things to David, he replied, \u201CHow
        can a poor man from a humble family afford the bride price for the daughter
        of a king?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Saul\u2019s men reported this back to the king, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he told them, \u201CTell David that all I want for the bride price
        is 100 Philistine foreskins! Vengeance on my enemies is all I really want.\u201D
        But what Saul had in mind was that David would be killed in the fight.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David was delighted to accept the offer. Before the time limit expired, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he and his men went out and killed 200 Philistines. Then David fulfilled
        the king\u2019s requirement by presenting all their foreskins to him. So
        Saul gave his daughter Michal to David to be his wife.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul realized that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was with
        David and how much his daughter Michal loved him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul became even more afraid of him, and he remained David\u2019s
        enemy for the rest of his life.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Saul Tries to Kill David
      content: '  Saul now urged his servants and his son Jonathan to assassinate
        David. But Jonathan, because of his strong affection for David, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "told him what his father was planning. \u201CTomorrow morning,\u201D
        he warned him, \u201Cyou must find a hiding place out in the fields. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I\u2019ll ask my father to go out there with me, and I\u2019ll talk
        to him about you. Then I\u2019ll tell you everything I can find out.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The next morning Jonathan spoke with his father about David, saying
        many good things about him. \u201CThe king must not sin against his servant
        David,\u201D Jonathan said. \u201CHe\u2019s never done anything to harm you.
        He has always helped you in any way he could. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Have you forgotten about the time he risked his life to kill the
        Philistine giant and how the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> brought a great
        victory to all Israel as a result? You were certainly happy about it then.
        Why should you murder an innocent man like David? There is no reason for
        it at all!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Saul listened to Jonathan and vowed, \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives, David will not be killed.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Afterward Jonathan called David and told him what had happened. Then
        he brought David to Saul, and David served in the court as before.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'War broke out again after that, and David led his troops against
        the Philistines. He attacked them with such fury that they all ran away.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But one day when Saul was sitting at home, with spear in hand, the
        tormenting spirit[[COMMENT(0)]] from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> suddenly
        came upon him again. As David played his harp, '
      comments:
      - number: '19:9 '
        content: Or <b>evil spirit.</b>
    - title: "Michal Saves David\u2019s Life"
      content: 'Saul hurled his spear at David. But David dodged out of the way,
        and leaving the spear stuck in the wall, he fled and escaped into the night.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul sent troops to watch David\u2019s house. They were told
        to kill David when he came out the next morning. But Michal, David\u2019s
        wife, warned him, \u201CIf you don\u2019t escape tonight, you will be dead
        by morning.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So she helped him climb out through a window, and he fled and escaped. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then she took an idol[[COMMENT(0)]] and put it in his bed, covered
        it with blankets, and put a cushion of goat\u2019s hair at its head.  "
      comments:
      - number: '19:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>teraphim; </b>also in 19:16.
    - title: 
      content: "When the troops came to arrest David, she told them he was sick and
        couldn\u2019t get out of bed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Saul sent the troops back to get David. He ordered, \u201CBring
        him to me in his bed so I can kill him!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when they came to carry David out, they discovered that it was
        only an idol in the bed with a cushion of goat\u2019s hair at its head.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy have you betrayed me like this and let my enemy escape?\u201D
        Saul demanded of Michal.\u201CI had to,\u201D Michal replied. \u201CHe threatened
        to kill me if I didn\u2019t help him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David escaped and went to Ramah to see Samuel, and he told him
        all that Saul had done to him. Then Samuel took David with him to live at
        Naioth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the report reached Saul that David was at Naioth in Ramah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he sent troops to capture him. But when they arrived and saw Samuel
        leading a group of prophets who were prophesying, the Spirit of God came
        upon Saul\u2019s men, and they also began to prophesy. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul heard what had happened, he sent other troops, but they,
        too, prophesied! The same thing happened a third time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, Saul himself went to Ramah and arrived at the great well
        in Secu. \u201CWhere are Samuel and David?\u201D he demanded.\u201CThey are
        at Naioth in Ramah,\u201D someone told him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But on the way to Naioth in Ramah the Spirit of God came even upon
        Saul, and he, too, began to prophesy all the way to Naioth! '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Jonathan Helps David
      content: "  David now fled from Naioth in Ramah and found Jonathan. \u201CWhat
        have I done?\u201D he exclaimed. \u201CWhat is my crime? How have I offended
        your father that he is so determined to kill me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThat\u2019s not true!\u201D Jonathan protested. \u201CYou\u2019re
        not going to die. He always tells me everything he\u2019s going to do, even
        the little things. I know my father wouldn\u2019t hide something like this
        from me. It just isn\u2019t so!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then David took an oath before Jonathan and said, \u201CYour father
        knows perfectly well about our friendship, so he has said to himself, \u2018I
        won\u2019t tell Jonathan\u2014why should I hurt him?\u2019 But I swear to
        you that I am only a step away from death! I swear it by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and by your own soul!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTell me what I can do to help you,\u201D Jonathan exclaimed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David replied, \u201CTomorrow we celebrate the new moon festival.
        I\u2019ve always eaten with the king on this occasion, but tomorrow I\u2019ll
        hide in the field and stay there until the evening of the third day. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If your father asks where I am, tell him I asked permission to go
        home to Bethlehem for an annual family sacrifice. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If he says, \u2018Fine!\u2019 you will know all is well. But if he
        is angry and loses his temper, you will know he is determined to kill me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Show me this loyalty as my sworn friend\u2014for we made a solemn
        pact before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2014or kill me yourself if I
        have sinned against your father. But please don\u2019t betray me to him!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNever!\u201D Jonathan exclaimed. \u201CYou know that if I had
        the slightest notion my father was planning to kill you, I would tell you
        at once.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then David asked, \u201CHow will I know whether or not your father
        is angry?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCome out to the field with me,\u201D Jonathan replied. And
        they went out there together. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jonathan told David, \u201CI promise by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, that by this time tomorrow, or the next day at the latest,
        I will talk to my father and let you know at once how he feels about you.
        If he speaks favorably about you, I will let you know. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if he is angry and wants you killed, may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        strike me and even kill me if I don\u2019t warn you so you can escape and
        live. May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> be with you as he used to be with
        my father. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And may you treat me with the faithful love of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        as long as I live. But if I die, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "treat my family with this faithful love, even when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        destroys all your enemies from the face of the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jonathan made a solemn pact with David,[[COMMENT(0)]] saying,
        \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> destroy all your enemies!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '20:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>with the house of David.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'And Jonathan made David reaffirm his vow of friendship again, for
        Jonathan loved David as he loved himself.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jonathan said, \u201CTomorrow we celebrate the new moon festival.
        You will be missed when your place at the table is empty. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The day after tomorrow, toward evening, go to the place where you
        hid before, and wait there by the stone pile.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the stone Ezel. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'I will come out and shoot three arrows to the side of the stone pile
        as though I were shooting at a target. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then I will send a boy to bring the arrows back. If you hear me tell
        him, \u2018They\u2019re on this side,\u2019 then you will know, as surely
        as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives, that all is well, and there is
        no trouble. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if I tell him, \u2018Go farther\u2014the arrows are still ahead
        of you,\u2019 then it will mean that you must leave immediately, for the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is sending you away. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> make us keep our promises
        to each other, for he has witnessed them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David hid himself in the field, and when the new moon festival
        began, the king sat down to eat. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He sat at his usual place against the wall, with Jonathan sitting
        opposite him[[COMMENT(0)]] and Abner beside him. But David\u2019s place was
        empty. "
      comments:
      - number: '20:25 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>with Jonathan standing.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Saul didn\u2019t say anything about it that day, for he said to himself,
        \u201CSomething must have made David ceremonially unclean.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when David\u2019s place was empty again the next day, Saul asked
        Jonathan, \u201CWhy hasn\u2019t the son of Jesse been here for the meal either
        yesterday or today?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jonathan replied, \u201CDavid earnestly asked me if he could go to
        Bethlehem. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said, \u2018Please let me go, for we are having a family sacrifice.
        My brother demanded that I be there. So please let me get away to see my
        brothers.\u2019 That\u2019s why he isn\u2019t here at the king\u2019s table.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul boiled with rage at Jonathan. \u201CYou stupid son of a whore!\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]
        he swore at him. \u201CDo you think I don\u2019t know that you want him to
        be king in your place, shaming yourself and your mother? "
      comments:
      - number: '20:30 '
        content: Hebrew <b>You son of a perverse and rebellious woman.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "As long as that son of Jesse is alive, you\u2019ll never be king.
        Now go and get him so I can kill him!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut why should he be put to death?\u201D Jonathan asked his
        father. \u201CWhat has he done?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Saul hurled his spear at Jonathan, intending to kill him. So
        at last Jonathan realized that his father was really determined to kill David.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jonathan left the table in fierce anger and refused to eat on that
        second day of the festival, for he was crushed by his father\u2019s shameful
        behavior toward David.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next morning, as agreed, Jonathan went out into the field and
        took a young boy with him to gather his arrows. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CStart running,\u201D he told the boy, \u201Cso you can find
        the arrows as I shoot them.\u201D So the boy ran, and Jonathan shot an arrow
        beyond him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the boy had almost reached the arrow, Jonathan shouted, \u201CThe
        arrow is still ahead of you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Hurry, hurry, don\u2019t wait.\u201D So the boy quickly gathered
        up the arrows and ran back to his master. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He, of course, suspected nothing; only Jonathan and David understood
        the signal. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jonathan gave his bow and arrows to the boy and told him to
        take them back to town.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as the boy was gone, David came out from where he had been
        hiding near the stone pile.[[COMMENT(0)]] Then David bowed three times to
        Jonathan with his face to the ground. Both of them were in tears as they
        embraced each other and said good-bye, especially David.  '
      comments:
      - number: '20:41 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>near the south edge.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: David Runs from Saul
      content: "    [[COMMENT(0)]]David went to the town of Nob to see Ahimelech
        the priest. Ahimelech trembled when he saw him. \u201CWhy are you alone?\u201D
        he asked. \u201CWhy is no one with you?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:1 '
        content: '  Verses 21:1-15 are numbered 21:2-16 in Hebrew text.  '
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe king has sent me on a private matter,\u201D David said.
        \u201CHe told me not to tell anyone why I am here. I have told my men where
        to meet me later. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now, what is there to eat? Give me five loaves of bread or anything
        else you have.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe don\u2019t have any regular bread,\u201D the priest replied.
        \u201CBut there is the holy bread, which you can have if your young men have
        not slept with any women recently.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t worry,\u201D David replied. \u201CI never allow
        my men to be with women when we are on a campaign. And since they stay clean
        even on ordinary trips, how much more on this one!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Since there was no other food available, the priest gave him the
        holy bread\u2014the Bread of the Presence that was placed before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        in the Tabernacle. It had just been replaced that day with fresh bread.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now Doeg the Edomite, Saul\u2019s chief herdsman, was there that
        day, having been detained before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:7 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "David asked Ahimelech, \u201CDo you have a spear or sword? The king\u2019s
        business was so urgent that I didn\u2019t even have time to grab a weapon!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI only have the sword of Goliath the Philistine, whom you killed
        in the valley of Elah,\u201D the priest replied. \u201CIt is wrapped in a
        cloth behind the ephod. Take that if you want it, for there is nothing else
        here.\u201D\u201CThere is nothing like it!\u201D David replied. \u201CGive
        it to me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David escaped from Saul and went to King Achish of Gath. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the officers of Achish were unhappy about his being there. \u201CIsn\u2019t
        this David, the king of the land?\u201D they asked. \u201CIsn\u2019t he the
        one the people honor with dances, singing,\u2018Saul has killed his thousands,and
        David his ten thousands\u2019?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David heard these comments and was very afraid of what King Achish
        of Gath might do to him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So he pretended to be insane, scratching on doors and drooling down
        his beard.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, King Achish said to his men, \u201CMust you bring me a madman? "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: David at the Cave of Adullam
      content: '  So David left Gath and escaped to the cave of Adullam. Soon his
        brothers and all his other relatives joined him there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then others began coming\u2014men who were in trouble or in debt
        or who were just discontented\u2014until David was the captain of about 400
        men.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Later David went to Mizpeh in Moab, where he asked the king, \u201CPlease
        allow my father and mother to live here with you until I know what God is
        going to do for me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So David\u2019s parents stayed in Moab with the king during the entire
        time David was living in his stronghold.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day the prophet Gad told David, \u201CLeave the stronghold and
        return to the land of Judah.\u201D So David went to the forest of Hereth.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The news of his arrival in Judah soon reached Saul. At the time,
        the king was sitting beneath the tamarisk tree on the hill at Gibeah, holding
        his spear and surrounded by his officers.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CListen here, you men of Benjamin!\u201D Saul shouted to his
        officers when he heard the news. \u201CHas that son of Jesse promised every
        one of you fields and vineyards? Has he promised to make you all generals
        and captains in his army?[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '22:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>commanders of thousands and commanders of hundreds?</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Is that why you have conspired against me? For not one of you told
        me when my own son made a solemn pact with the son of Jesse. You\u2019re
        not even sorry for me. Think of it! My own son\u2014encouraging him to kill
        me, as he is trying to do this very day!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Doeg the Edomite, who was standing there with Saul\u2019s men,
        spoke up. \u201CWhen I was at Nob,\u201D he said, \u201CI saw the son of
        Jesse talking to the priest, Ahimelech son of Ahitub. "
      comments: []
    - title: The Slaughter of the Priests
      content: "Ahimelech consulted the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> for him. Then
        he gave him food and the sword of Goliath the Philistine.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'King Saul immediately sent for Ahimelech and all his family, who
        served as priests at Nob. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they arrived, Saul shouted at him, \u201CListen to me, you son
        of Ahitub!\u201D\u201CWhat is it, my king?\u201D Ahimelech asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy have you and the son of Jesse conspired against me?\u201D
        Saul demanded. \u201CWhy did you give him food and a sword? Why have you
        consulted God for him? Why have you encouraged him to kill me, as he is trying
        to do this very day?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut sir,\u201D Ahimelech replied, \u201Cis anyone among all
        your servants as faithful as David, your son-in-law? Why, he is the captain
        of your bodyguard and a highly honored member of your household! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This was certainly not the first time I had consulted God for him!
        May the king not accuse me and my family in this matter, for I knew nothing
        at all of any plot against you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou will surely die, Ahimelech, along with your entire family!\u201D
        the king shouted. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he ordered his bodyguards, \u201CKill these priests of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        for they are allies and conspirators with David! They knew he was running
        away from me, but they didn\u2019t tell me!\u201D But Saul\u2019s men refused
        to kill the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s priests.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the king said to Doeg, \u201CYou do it.\u201D So Doeg the Edomite
        turned on them and killed them that day, eighty-five priests in all, still
        wearing their priestly garments. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he went to Nob, the town of the priests, and killed the priests\u2019
        families\u2014men and women, children and babies\u2014and all the cattle,
        donkeys, sheep, and goats.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Only Abiathar, one of the sons of Ahimelech, escaped and fled to
        David. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When he told David that Saul had killed the priests of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David exclaimed, \u201CI knew it! When I saw Doeg the Edomite there
        that day, I knew he was sure to tell Saul. Now I have caused the death of
        all your father\u2019s family. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: David Protects the Town of Keilah
      content: '  One day news came to David that the Philistines were at Keilah
        stealing grain from the threshing floors. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CShould I go and
        attack them?\u201D\u201CYes, go and save Keilah,\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But David\u2019s men said, \u201CWe\u2019re afraid even here in Judah.
        We certainly don\u2019t want to go to Keilah to fight the whole Philistine
        army!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So David asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> again, and again the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CGo down to Keilah, for I will
        help you conquer the Philistines.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David and his men went to Keilah. They slaughtered the Philistines
        and took all their livestock and rescued the people of Keilah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now when Abiathar son of Ahimelech fled to David at Keilah, he brought
        the ephod with him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul soon learned that David was at Keilah. \u201CGood!\u201D he
        exclaimed. \u201CWe\u2019ve got him now! God has handed him over to me, for
        he has trapped himself in a walled town!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Saul mobilized his entire army to march to Keilah and besiege
        David and his men.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But David learned of Saul\u2019s plan and told Abiathar the priest
        to bring the ephod and ask the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> what he should
        do. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then David prayed, \u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of Israel,
        I have heard that Saul is planning to come and destroy Keilah because I am
        here. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Will the leaders of Keilah betray me to him?[[COMMENT(0)]] And will
        Saul actually come as I have heard? O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of
        Israel, please tell me.\u201DAnd the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CHe
        will come.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:11 '
        content: Some manuscripts lack the first sentence of 23:11.
    - title: David Hides in the Wilderness
      content: "Again David asked, \u201CWill the leaders of Keilah betray me and
        my men to Saul?\u201DAnd the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CYes,
        they will betray you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So David and his men\u2014about 600 of them now\u2014left Keilah
        and began roaming the countryside. Word soon reached Saul that David had
        escaped, so he didn\u2019t go to Keilah after all. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David now stayed in the strongholds of the wilderness and in the
        hill country of Ziph. Saul hunted him day after day, but God didn\u2019t
        let Saul find him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day near Horesh, David received the news that Saul was on the
        way to Ziph to search for him and kill him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jonathan went to find David and encouraged him to stay strong in
        his faith in God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,\u201D Jonathan reassured him. \u201CMy
        father will never find you! You are going to be the king of Israel, and I
        will be next to you, as my father, Saul, is well aware.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the two of them renewed their solemn pact before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        Then Jonathan returned home, while David stayed at Horesh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now the men of Ziph went to Saul in Gibeah and betrayed David
        to him. \u201CWe know where David is hiding,\u201D they said. \u201CHe is
        in the strongholds of Horesh on the hill of Hakilah, which is in the southern
        part of Jeshimon. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Come down whenever you\u2019re ready, O king, and we will catch him
        and hand him over to you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> bless you,\u201D Saul said.
        \u201CAt last someone is concerned about me! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Go and check again to be sure of where he is staying and who has
        seen him there, for I know that he is very crafty. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Discover his hiding places, and come back when you are sure. Then
        I\u2019ll go with you. And if he is in the area at all, I\u2019ll track him
        down, even if I have to search every hiding place in Judah!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the men of Ziph returned home ahead of Saul.Meanwhile, David and
        his men had moved into the wilderness of Maon in the Arabah Valley south
        of Jeshimon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When David heard that Saul and his men were searching for him, he
        went even farther into the wilderness to the great rock, and he remained
        there in the wilderness of Maon. But Saul kept after him in the wilderness.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul and David were now on opposite sides of a mountain. Just as
        Saul and his men began to close in on David and his men, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'an urgent message reached Saul that the Philistines were raiding
        Israel again. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Saul quit chasing David and returned to fight the Philistines.
        Ever since that time, the place where David was camped has been called the
        Rock of Escape.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '23:28 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Sela-hammahlekoth.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: "David Spares Saul\u2019s Life"
      content: '    [[COMMENT(0)]]After Saul returned from fighting the Philistines,
        he was told that David had gone into the wilderness of En-gedi. '
      comments:
      - number: '24:1 '
        content: '  Verses 24:1-22 are numbered 24:2-23 in Hebrew text.  '
    - title: 
      content: 'So Saul chose 3,000 elite troops from all Israel and went to search
        for David and his men near the rocks of the wild goats.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At the place where the road passes some sheepfolds, Saul went into
        a cave to relieve himself. But as it happened, David and his men were hiding
        farther back in that very cave!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow\u2019s your opportunity!\u201D David\u2019s men whispered
        to him. \u201CToday the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is telling you, \u2018I
        will certainly put your enemy into your power, to do with as you wish.\u2019\u201D
        So David crept forward and cut off a piece of the hem of Saul\u2019s robe.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But then David\u2019s conscience began bothering him because he had
        cut Saul\u2019s robe. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said to his men, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> forbid
        that I should do this to my lord the king. I shouldn\u2019t attack the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anointed one, for the <smallcaps>Lord </smallcaps>himself has chosen him.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David restrained his men and did not let them kill Saul.After
        Saul had left the cave and gone on his way, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David came out and shouted after him, \u201CMy lord the king!\u201D
        And when Saul looked around, David bowed low before him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he shouted to Saul, \u201CWhy do you listen to the people who
        say I am trying to harm you? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This very day you can see with your own eyes it isn\u2019t true.
        For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> placed you at my mercy back there in
        the cave. Some of my men told me to kill you, but I spared you. For I said,
        \u2018I will never harm the king\u2014he is the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anointed one.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Look, my father, at what I have in my hand. It is a piece of the
        hem of your robe! I cut it off, but I didn\u2019t kill you. This proves that
        I am not trying to harm you and that I have not sinned against you, even
        though you have been hunting for me to kill me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> judge between us. Perhaps
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will punish you for what you are trying to
        do to me, but I will never harm you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As that old proverb says, \u2018From evil people come evil deeds.\u2019
        So you can be sure I will never harm you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Who is the king of Israel trying to catch anyway? Should he spend
        his time chasing one who is as worthless as a dead dog or a single flea? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> therefore judge which of us is
        right and punish the guilty one. He is my advocate, and he will rescue me
        from your power!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When David had finished speaking, Saul called back, \u201CIs that
        really you, my son David?\u201D Then he began to cry. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he said to David, \u201CYou are a better man than I am, for you
        have repaid me good for evil. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yes, you have been amazingly kind to me today, for when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        put me in a place where you could have killed me, you didn\u2019t do it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Who else would let his enemy get away when he had him in his power?
        May the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> reward you well for the kindness you
        have shown me today. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And now I realize that you are surely going to be king, and that
        the kingdom of Israel will flourish under your rule. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now swear to me by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> that when that
        happens you will not kill my family and destroy my line of descendants!\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Death of SamuelNabal Angers David
      content: '  Now Samuel died, and all Israel gathered for his funeral. They
        buried him at his house in Ramah.Then David moved down to the wilderness
        of Maon.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:1 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 25:2); Hebrew reads <b>Paran.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'There was a wealthy man from Maon who owned property near the town
        of Carmel. He had 3,000 sheep and 1,000 goats, and it was sheep-shearing
        time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This man\u2019s name was Nabal, and his wife, Abigail, was a sensible
        and beautiful woman. But Nabal, a descendant of Caleb, was crude and mean
        in all his dealings.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When David heard that Nabal was shearing his sheep, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'he sent ten of his young men to Carmel with this message for Nabal: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPeace and prosperity to you, your family, and everything you
        own! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I am told that it is sheep-shearing time. While your shepherds stayed
        among us near Carmel, we never harmed them, and nothing was ever stolen from
        them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Ask your own men, and they will tell you this is true. So would you
        be kind to us, since we have come at a time of celebration? Please share
        any provisions you might have on hand with us and with your friend David.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David\u2019s young men gave this message to Nabal in David\u2019s
        name, and they waited for a reply.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho is this fellow David?\u201D Nabal sneered to the young
        men. \u201CWho does this son of Jesse think he is? There are lots of servants
        these days who run away from their masters. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Should I take my bread and my water and my meat that I\u2019ve slaughtered
        for my shearers and give it to a band of outlaws who come from who knows
        where?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So David\u2019s young men returned and told him what Nabal had said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGet your swords!\u201D was David\u2019s reply as he strapped
        on his own. Then 400 men started off with David, and 200 remained behind
        to guard their equipment.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, one of Nabal\u2019s servants went to Abigail and told
        her, \u201CDavid sent messengers from the wilderness to greet our master,
        but he screamed insults at them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These men have been very good to us, and we never suffered any harm
        from them. Nothing was stolen from us the whole time they were with us. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In fact, day and night they were like a wall of protection to us
        and the sheep. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You need to know this and figure out what to do, for there is going
        to be trouble for our master and his whole family. He\u2019s so ill-tempered
        that no one can even talk to him!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abigail wasted no time. She quickly gathered 200 loaves of bread,
        two wineskins full of wine, five sheep that had been slaughtered, nearly
        a bushel[[COMMENT(0)]] of roasted grain, 100 clusters of raisins, and 200
        fig cakes. She packed them on donkeys '
      comments:
      - number: '25:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>5 seahs </b>[36.5 liters].
    - title: 
      content: "and said to her servants, \u201CGo on ahead. I will follow you shortly.\u201D
        But she didn\u2019t tell her husband Nabal what she was doing.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As she was riding her donkey into a mountain ravine, she saw David
        and his men coming toward her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David had just been saying, \u201CA lot of good it did to help this
        fellow. We protected his flocks in the wilderness, and nothing he owned was
        lost or stolen. But he has repaid me evil for good. "
      comments: []
    - title: Abigail Intercedes for Nabal
      content: "May God strike me and kill me[[COMMENT(0)]] if even one man of his
        household is still alive tomorrow morning!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:22 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>May God strike and kill the
          enemies of David.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'When Abigail saw David, she quickly got off her donkey and bowed
        low before him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She fell at his feet and said, \u201CI accept all blame in this matter,
        my lord. Please listen to what I have to say. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I know Nabal is a wicked and ill-tempered man; please don\u2019t
        pay any attention to him. He is a fool, just as his name suggests.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        But I never even saw the young men you sent.  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:25 '
        content: "The name <b>Nabal </b>means \u201Cfool.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow, my lord, as surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        lives and you yourself live, since the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has kept
        you from murdering and taking vengeance into your own hands, let all your
        enemies and those who try to harm you be as cursed as Nabal is. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And here is a present that I, your servant, have brought to you and
        your young men. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Please forgive me if I have offended you in any way. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will surely reward you with a lasting dynasty, for you are fighting the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        battles. And you have not done wrong throughout your entire life.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CEven when you are chased by those who seek to kill you, your
        life is safe in the care of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God, secure
        in his treasure pouch! But the lives of your enemies will disappear like
        stones shot from a sling! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has done all he promised and
        has made you leader of Israel, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "don\u2019t let this be a blemish on your record. Then your conscience
        won\u2019t have to bear the staggering burden of needless bloodshed and vengeance.
        And when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has done these great things for
        you, please remember me, your servant!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David replied to Abigail, \u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        the God of Israel, who has sent you to meet me today! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Thank God for your good sense! Bless you for keeping me from murder
        and from carrying out vengeance with my own hands. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For I swear by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of Israel,
        who has kept me from hurting you, that if you had not hurried out to meet
        me, not one of Nabal\u2019s men would still be alive tomorrow morning.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then David accepted her present and told her, \u201CReturn home in
        peace. I have heard what you said. We will not kill your husband.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Abigail arrived home, she found that Nabal was throwing a big
        party and was celebrating like a king. He was very drunk, so she didn\u2019t
        tell him anything about her meeting with David until dawn the next day. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the morning when Nabal was sober, his wife told him what had happened.
        As a result he had a stroke,[[COMMENT(0)]] and he lay paralyzed on his bed
        like a stone. '
      comments:
      - number: '25:37 '
        content: Hebrew <b>his heart failed him.</b>
    - title: David Marries Abigail
      content: 'About ten days later, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> struck him,
        and he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When David heard that Nabal was dead, he said, \u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who has avenged the insult I received from Nabal and has kept me from doing
        it myself. Nabal has received the punishment for his sin.\u201D Then David
        sent messengers to Abigail to ask her to become his wife.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the messengers arrived at Carmel, they told Abigail, \u201CDavid
        has sent us to take you back to marry him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She bowed low to the ground and responded, \u201CI, your servant,
        would be happy to marry David. I would even be willing to become a slave,
        washing the feet of his servants!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Quickly getting ready, she took along five of her servant girls as
        attendants, mounted her donkey, and went with David\u2019s messengers. And
        so she became his wife. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David also married Ahinoam from Jezreel, making both of them his
        wives. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: David Spares Saul Again
      content: "  Now some men from Ziph came to Saul at Gibeah to tell him, \u201CDavid
        is hiding on the hill of Hakilah, which overlooks Jeshimon.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Saul took 3,000 of Israel\u2019s elite troops and went to hunt
        him down in the wilderness of Ziph. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Saul camped along the road beside the hill of Hakilah, near Jeshimon,
        where David was hiding. When David learned that Saul had come after him into
        the wilderness, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "he sent out spies to verify the report of Saul\u2019s arrival.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David slipped over to Saul\u2019s camp one night to look around.
        Saul and Abner son of Ner, the commander of his army, were sleeping inside
        a ring formed by the slumbering warriors. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho will volunteer to go in there with me?\u201D David asked
        Ahimelech the Hittite and Abishai son of Zeruiah, Joab\u2019s brother.\u201CI\u2019ll
        go with you,\u201D Abishai replied. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So David and Abishai went right into Saul\u2019s camp and found him
        asleep, with his spear stuck in the ground beside his head. Abner and the
        soldiers were lying asleep around him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGod has surely handed your enemy over to you this time!\u201D
        Abishai whispered to David. \u201CLet me pin him to the ground with one thrust
        of the spear; I won\u2019t need to strike twice!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo!\u201D David said. \u201CDon\u2019t kill him. For who can
        remain innocent after attacking the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anointed
        one? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Surely the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will strike Saul down someday,
        or he will die of old age or in battle. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> forbid that I should kill the one
        he has anointed! But take his spear and that jug of water beside his head,
        and then let\u2019s get out of here!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So David took the spear and jug of water that were near Saul\u2019s
        head. Then he and Abishai got away without anyone seeing them or even waking
        up, because the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had put Saul\u2019s men into
        a deep sleep.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David climbed the hill opposite the camp until he was at a safe distance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he shouted down to the soldiers and to Abner son of Ner, \u201CWake
        up, Abner!\u201D\u201CWho is it?\u201D Abner demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWell, Abner, you\u2019re a great man, aren\u2019t you?\u201D
        David taunted. \u201CWhere in all Israel is there anyone as mighty? So why
        haven\u2019t you guarded your master the king when someone came to kill him? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This isn\u2019t good at all! I swear by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        that you and your men deserve to die, because you failed to protect your
        master, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s anointed! Look around! Where
        are the king\u2019s spear and the jug of water that were beside his head?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul recognized David\u2019s voice and called out, \u201CIs that
        you, my son David?\u201DAnd David replied, \u201CYes, my lord the king. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Why are you chasing me? What have I done? What is my crime? '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now let my lord the king listen to his servant. If the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has stirred you up against me, then let him accept my offering. But if this
        is simply a human scheme, then may those involved be cursed by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        For they have driven me from my home, so I can no longer live among the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        people, and they have said, \u2018Go, worship pagan gods.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Must I die on foreign soil, far from the presence of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>?
        Why has the king of Israel come out to search for a single flea? Why does
        he hunt me down like a partridge on the mountains?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Saul confessed, \u201CI have sinned. Come back home, my son,
        and I will no longer try to harm you, for you valued my life today. I have
        been a fool and very, very wrong.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHere is your spear, O king,\u201D David replied. \u201CLet
        one of your young men come over and get it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> gives his own reward for doing good
        and for being loyal, and I refused to kill you even when the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        placed you in my power, for you are the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        anointed one. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now may the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> value my life, even as I
        have valued yours today. May he rescue me from all my troubles.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: David among the Philistines
      content: "  But David kept thinking to himself, \u201CSomeday Saul is going
        to get me. The best thing I can do is escape to the Philistines. Then Saul
        will stop hunting for me in Israelite territory, and I will finally be safe.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David took his 600 men and went over and joined Achish son of
        Maoch, the king of Gath. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David and his men and their families settled there with Achish at
        Gath. David brought his two wives along with him\u2014Ahinoam from Jezreel
        and Abigail, Nabal\u2019s widow from Carmel. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Word soon reached Saul that David had fled to Gath, so he stopped
        hunting for him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day David said to Achish, \u201CIf it is all right with you,
        we would rather live in one of the country towns instead of here in the royal
        city.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Achish gave him the town of Ziklag (which still belongs to the
        kings of Judah to this day), '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and they lived there among the Philistines for a year and four months.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David and his men spent their time raiding the Geshurites, the Girzites,
        and the Amalekites\u2014people who had lived near Shur, toward the land of
        Egypt, since ancient times. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David did not leave one person alive in the villages he attacked.
        He took the sheep, goats, cattle, donkeys, camels, and clothing before returning
        home to see King Achish.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhere did you make your raid today?\u201D Achish would ask.And
        David would reply, \u201CAgainst the south of Judah, the Jerahmeelites, and
        the Kenites.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'No one was left alive to come to Gath and tell where he had really
        been. This happened again and again while he was living among the Philistines. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Saul Consults a Medium
      content: "  About that time the Philistines mustered their armies for another
        war with Israel. King Achish told David, \u201CYou and your men will be expected
        to join me in battle.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CVery well!\u201D David agreed. \u201CNow you will see for yourself
        what we can do.\u201DThen Achish told David, \u201CI will make you my personal
        bodyguard for life.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, Samuel had died, and all Israel had mourned for him. He
        was buried in Ramah, his hometown. And Saul had banned from the land of Israel
        all mediums and those who consult the spirits of the dead.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Philistines set up their camp at Shunem, and Saul gathered all
        the army of Israel and camped at Gilboa. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Saul saw the vast Philistine army, he became frantic with fear. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> what he should do, but the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> refused to answer him, either by dreams or by
        sacred lots[[COMMENT(0)]] or by the prophets. '
      comments:
      - number: '28:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>by Urim.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Saul then said to his advisers, \u201CFind a woman who is a medium,
        so I can go and ask her what to do.\u201DHis advisers replied, \u201CThere
        is a medium at Endor.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Saul disguised himself by wearing ordinary clothing instead of
        his royal robes. Then he went to the woman\u2019s home at night, accompanied
        by two of his men.\u201CI have to talk to a man who has died,\u201D he said.
        \u201CWill you call up his spirit for me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAre you trying to get me killed?\u201D the woman demanded.
        \u201CYou know that Saul has outlawed all the mediums and all who consult
        the spirits of the dead. Why are you setting a trap for me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Saul took an oath in the name of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        and promised, \u201CAs surely as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> lives, nothing
        bad will happen to you for doing this.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, the woman said, \u201CWell, whose spirit do you want me
        to call up?\u201D\u201CCall up Samuel,\u201D Saul replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the woman saw Samuel, she screamed, \u201CYou\u2019ve deceived
        me! You are Saul!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be afraid!\u201D the king told her. \u201CWhat do
        you see?\u201D\u201CI see a god[[COMMENT(0)]] coming up out of the earth,\u201D
        she said.  "
      comments:
      - number: '28:13 '
        content: Or <b>gods.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat does he look like?\u201D Saul asked.\u201CHe is an old
        man wrapped in a robe,\u201D she replied. Saul realized it was Samuel, and
        he fell to the ground before him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy have you disturbed me by calling me back?\u201D Samuel
        asked Saul.\u201CBecause I am in deep trouble,\u201D Saul replied. \u201CThe
        Philistines are at war with me, and God has left me and won\u2019t reply
        by prophets or dreams. So I have called for you to tell me what to do.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Samuel replied, \u201CWhy ask me, since the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has left you and has become your enemy? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has done just as he said he would.
        He has torn the kingdom from you and given it to your rival, David. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has done this to you today because
        you refused to carry out his fierce anger against the Amalekites. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What\u2019s more, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will hand you and
        the army of Israel over to the Philistines tomorrow, and you and your sons
        will be here with me. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will bring down the
        entire army of Israel in defeat.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul fell full length on the ground, paralyzed with fright because
        of Samuel\u2019s words. He was also faint with hunger, for he had eaten nothing
        all day and all night.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the woman saw how distraught he was, she said, \u201CSir, I
        obeyed your command at the risk of my life. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now do what I say, and let me give you a little something to eat
        so you can regain your strength for the trip back.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Saul refused to eat anything. Then his advisers joined the woman
        in urging him to eat, so he finally yielded and got up from the ground and
        sat on the couch.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The woman had been fattening a calf, so she hurried out and killed
        it. She took some flour, kneaded it into dough and baked unleavened bread. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Philistines Reject David
      content: '  The entire Philistine army now mobilized at Aphek, and the Israelites
        camped at the spring in Jezreel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As the Philistine rulers were leading out their troops in groups
        of hundreds and thousands, David and his men marched at the rear with King
        Achish. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the Philistine commanders demanded, \u201CWhat are these Hebrews
        doing here?\u201DAnd Achish told them, \u201CThis is David, the servant of
        King Saul of Israel. He\u2019s been with me for years, and I\u2019ve never
        found a single fault in him from the day he arrived until today.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the Philistine commanders were angry. \u201CSend him back to
        the town you\u2019ve given him!\u201D they demanded. \u201CHe can\u2019t
        go into the battle with us. What if he turns against us in battle and becomes
        our adversary? Is there any better way for him to reconcile himself with
        his master than by handing our heads over to him? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isn\u2019t this the same David about whom the women of Israel sing
        in their dances,\u2018Saul has killed his thousands,and David his ten thousands\u2019?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Achish finally summoned David and said to him, \u201CI swear by
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> that you have been a trustworthy ally. I
        think you should go with me into battle, for I\u2019ve never found a single
        flaw in you from the day you arrived until today. But the other Philistine
        rulers won\u2019t hear of it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Please don\u2019t upset them, but go back quietly.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat have I done to deserve this treatment?\u201D David demanded.
        \u201CWhat have you ever found in your servant, that I can\u2019t go and
        fight the enemies of my lord the king?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Achish insisted, \u201CAs far as I\u2019m concerned, you\u2019re
        as perfect as an angel of God. But the Philistine commanders are afraid to
        have you with them in the battle. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now get up early in the morning, and leave with your men as soon
        as it gets light.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: David Destroys the Amalekites
      content: '  Three days later, when David and his men arrived home at their
        town of Ziklag, they found that the Amalekites had made a raid into the Negev
        and Ziklag; they had crushed Ziklag and burned it to the ground. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They had carried off the women and children and everyone else but
        without killing anyone.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When David and his men saw the ruins and realized what had happened
        to their families, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'they wept until they could weep no more. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "David\u2019s two wives, Ahinoam from Jezreel and Abigail, the widow
        of Nabal from Carmel, were among those captured. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David was now in great danger because all his men were very bitter
        about losing their sons and daughters, and they began to talk of stoning
        him. But David found strength in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> his God.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to Abiathar the priest, \u201CBring me the ephod!\u201D
        So Abiathar brought it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then David asked the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CShould I
        chase after this band of raiders? Will I catch them?\u201DAnd the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        told him, \u201CYes, go after them. You will surely recover everything that
        was taken from you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So David and his 600 men set out, and they came to the brook Besor. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But 200 of the men were too exhausted to cross the brook, so David
        continued the pursuit with 400 men.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Along the way they found an Egyptian man in a field and brought him
        to David. They gave him some bread to eat and water to drink. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They also gave him part of a fig cake and two clusters of raisins,
        for he hadn\u2019t had anything to eat or drink for three days and nights.
        Before long his strength returned.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTo whom do you belong, and where do you come from?\u201D David
        asked him.\u201CI am an Egyptian\u2014the slave of an Amalekite,\u201D he
        replied. \u201CMy master abandoned me three days ago because I was sick. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We were on our way back from raiding the Kerethites in the Negev,
        the territory of Judah, and the land of Caleb, and we had just burned Ziklag.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWill you lead me to this band of raiders?\u201D David asked.The
        young man replied, \u201CIf you take an oath in God\u2019s name that you
        will not kill me or give me back to my master, then I will guide you to them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So he led David to them, and they found the Amalekites spread out
        across the fields, eating and drinking and dancing with joy because of the
        vast amount of plunder they had taken from the Philistines and the land of
        Judah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David and his men rushed in among them and slaughtered them throughout
        that night and the entire next day until evening. None of the Amalekites
        escaped except 400 young men who fled on camels. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'David got back everything the Amalekites had taken, and he rescued
        his two wives. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Nothing was missing: small or great, son or daughter, nor anything
        else that had been taken. David brought everything back. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He also recovered all the flocks and herds, and his men drove them
        ahead of the other livestock. \u201CThis plunder belongs to David!\u201D
        they said.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then David returned to the brook Besor and met up with the 200 men
        who had been left behind because they were too exhausted to go with him.
        They went out to meet David and his men, and David greeted them joyfully. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But some evil troublemakers among David\u2019s men said, \u201CThey
        didn\u2019t go with us, so they can\u2019t have any of the plunder we recovered.
        Give them their wives and children, and tell them to be gone.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But David said, \u201CNo, my brothers! Don\u2019t be selfish with
        what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has given us. He has kept us safe and
        helped us defeat the band of raiders that attacked us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Who will listen when you talk like this? We share and share alike\u2014those
        who go to battle and those who guard the equipment.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From then on David made this a decree and regulation for Israel,
        and it is still followed today.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When he arrived at Ziklag, David sent part of the plunder to the
        elders of Judah, who were his friends. \u201CHere is a present for you, taken
        from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s enemies,\u201D he said.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The gifts were sent to the people of the following towns David had
        visited: Bethel, Ramoth-negev, Jattir, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Aroer, Siphmoth, Eshtemoa, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Racal,[[COMMENT(0)]] the towns of the Jerahmeelites, the towns of
        the Kenites, '
      comments:
      - number: '30:29 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>Carmel.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Hormah, Bor-ashan, Athach, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Death of Saul
      content: '  Now the Philistines attacked Israel, and the men of Israel fled
        before them. Many were slaughtered on the slopes of Mount Gilboa. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The Philistines closed in on Saul and his sons, and they killed three
        of his sons\u2014Jonathan, Abinadab, and Malkishua. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The fighting grew very fierce around Saul, and the Philistine archers
        caught up with him and wounded him severely.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Saul groaned to his armor bearer, \u201CTake your sword and kill
        me before these pagan Philistines come to run me through and taunt and torture
        me.\u201DBut his armor bearer was afraid and would not do it. So Saul took
        his own sword and fell on it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When his armor bearer realized that Saul was dead, he fell on his
        own sword and died beside the king. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Saul, his three sons, his armor bearer, and his troops all died
        together that same day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the Israelites on the other side of the Jezreel Valley and beyond
        the Jordan saw that the Israelite army had fled and that Saul and his sons
        were dead, they abandoned their towns and fled. So the Philistines moved
        in and occupied their towns.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next day, when the Philistines went out to strip the dead, they
        found the bodies of Saul and his three sons on Mount Gilboa. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they cut off Saul\u2019s head and stripped off his armor. Then
        they proclaimed the good news of Saul\u2019s death in their pagan temple
        and to the people throughout the land of Philistia. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They placed his armor in the temple of the Ashtoreths, and they fastened
        his body to the wall of the city of Beth-shan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the people of Jabesh-gilead heard what the Philistines had
        done to Saul, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'all their mighty warriors traveled through the night to Beth-shan
        and took the bodies of Saul and his sons down from the wall. They brought
        them to Jabesh, where they burned the bodies. '
      comments: []
